animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 4/28/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Patches and Maguire were put in CPR's fence overnight.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs?
Weight: 58 lb
Height: 23 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Patches needs a home with owners that know how to shape a young dog into a lovable house pet! Patches is dog selective- he gets along with some dogs but not others. Patches prefers to be the only apple of someone's eye. We have not tested Patches with kids. Patches loves to be outside and run in the field. He needs a home that will provide him with a safe space to explore outside. Patches is looking for a home as an only dog with no cats.

What is my personality like? We do not know much about Patches' past, but we do know he was loved. Patches and his brother Maguire were dropped off inside our gate overnight and left with a note asking us to please take care of them. We believe they were well loved, but not able to be cared for financially.

Patches is a young dog with lots of potential, he just needs a patient owner willing to work with him. He is strong willed and will need a strong leader to teach him some manners. Patches is high energy and needs an outlet for that. He will need daily exercise. Patches is highly intelligent and needs a "job" to do, whether it's playing or working alongside his owner on a farm.

Patches no absolutely no manners, but don't let this scare you away! What Patches lacks in household manners, he makes up for with a willing mind and open heart ready to learn.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Patches loves all people, but can be wary of other dogs. He is also terrified of the vacuum cleaner!

Other tips and tidbits: Patches' estimated birthday is 5/23/18.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
11/11/2020
Giorgio is originally from a hoarding situation.  He does not currently allow human touch.. He is really a sweet boy. you don’t know he’s in the house because he doesn’t wanna come near anybody. He is quiet and housebroken. If it was up to him he’d be outside 24/7 despite cold weather. If he can learn to cuddle and let people pet him he will be a perfect dog. I think it’s just gonna take a long time. Needs to be adopted into a home with another dog to an individual or couple that wants to help him learn to trust and is patient.

7/22/20

Hi, My name is Giorgio - I am thought to be a 3 year old neutered chihuahua mix.  I have been in foster care for over a month now,  I am house trained, get along with other dogs and kids.  Cats are unknown, but if I was a betting man, I'd say I'd be fine with them.   I am slowly starting to be a dog, after a rough start in my foster home where I didn't want anyone to touch me or be near me, I am starting to come around now.   I sleep in bed with my foster dad and his three dogs.  I feel like I am one of the pack (I know it's temporary) - But I would love, in fact, I probably need another dog or dogs to help me out in life.   I feel most at ease with another dog or dogs with me in a house. I love to chase balls in the backyard and can hang with the resident dogs that are all over 40 lbs each.  I also love to do rolly pollies in the grass on hot days in the sun.  I also love to crawl up and cuddle one of my dog friends while my foster dad watches TV at night.  My heartworm treatment is going well, I am done with the 30 days of antibiotics and half way through my first month of heartworm preventative. Next month, I start injections and crate rest to get better and get rid of the worms in my heart. I still really don't like to be touched that much, but I tolerate it and while I'm cuddling on the couch or in the bed, I allow touches without any fuss.   I've done a complete 180 from my first days here and know humans aren't all that bad now - I continue to make progress and some day hope to trust all humans.  I have a lot of love to give in a tiny package - Won't you give me a chance and let me be your forever dog???


6/23/2020
Hi - my name is Giorgio - I used to be held up in a house with 50 other chichuahuas and that life was rough,  I made my way to Pennsylvania a few weeks ago and life is looking up.   I am a spunky little Chihuahua mix with lots of personality once I let you see it.   I am very timid at first and do not like to be touched excessively.  I will tolerate a pet here and there but i prefer to be seen and heard, but not touched for now.   I am sure once I get to know you - I will want lots of love and affection.   I been in my foster families house in PA for 2 weeks now and I am making small, but steady improvements.   To top it all off - I am Heartworm positive - but thats not a death sentence and many make a full recovery.   I am about 15 days into my antibiotic treatment, then will need injections to kill the worms in my heart, then lots of crate rest for a few months.  I have a lot of love to give - Are you willing to take a chance on me and help me out with a forever home and a place to recuperate from my heart worms??  Wags will even pay for the procedure at a vet of their choosing, or give you a credit towards choosing your own vet.
5/23/2020
Meet Giorgio T Dalton!!!  This incredibly sweet and shy boy is looking for his forever family. I am a handsome boy with a adorable tan and white coat. He is thought to be a 3 year old, neutered chi mix. 



  To begin the adoption process please, fill out our online application. Go to wagsrescue.com and click on adoption form.
Please call Susan @ 267-312-3372 if you have questions.

animal.description:
Those ears! That tail! Sugar is a sweet 1 year old momma dog who has come a long way in our care. She was a feral doggo who was very pregnant (7 puppies!) when she was rescued. All of her babies are finished nursing and are up for adoption. Shes ready to find her furever family too! Sugar is such a loving girl once she gets to know you. Correction, shes a TOTAL love bug once she gets to know you! She can be very shy at first because shes still learning that humans arent all terrifying! After a little time with you, shell be your girl! We are currently working on leash training and are teaching her not to jump when excited. Sugar can share a home with cats and bunnies as she doesnt pay them much attention at all! Shes house trained. Shes good with children that she knows, dogs and cats. Overall, Sugar is a wonderful girl who just needs to find the right family who will be patient with her as she learns to trust you. Shes a laid back lady but will play. She would rather be beside you, interested in whatever it is youre up to! She does require a fenced yard and a family that doesn't want to bring her out in public often. Does this sweetheart sound like a good match for your family? If so, please submit an adoption application so we can schedule a meet n greet!

The adoption fee for this pretty girl is $225. She has been spayed, microchipped and is up to date on vaccines!

animal.description:
Little John is a spunky little rat terrier who lives for walks and treats.  He starts his day off with a cute crawl towards his foster mom to give morning kisses - he is such a cuddle bug!  As a 2-year old pup, Little John is a bit of a wild child with high energy and curiosity.  He would do best in a home that can keep up with that energy, which includes one long walk a day (or more) and some entertainment along the way.

In true terrier fashion, he has a lot to say and he says it often so apartment living would not be the best home for him.  He is protective of his food and toys so we would recommend children 16+ who will respect his wishes/boundaries.  He is fearful of strangers and can occasionally become nippy if pushed,  so slow introductions done at his pace will be necessary. Little John hasn’t learned to accept other dogs so we are asking that he be the only pet in the home.

If you are interested in applying to adopt Little John, please fill out an application at www.maggiesmissionrescue.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Paloma is a female Boxer mix rescued in Texas. Our veterinary partner estimates that Paloma is 5 years old at the time of intake in May 2020. Paloma is good with people of all ages and other dogs. You can see the heartbreak in Paloma's eyes which tell the story of a loveless life of neglect and abuse at the end of a short, heavy logging chain. But when we convinced Paloma's owner to surrender her to us, we saw a sparkle in Paloma's eye that was never there before. Paloma's story becomes even sadder as once we rescued Paloma, we discovered this senior girl was pregnant. Again. None of Paloma's puppies survived as a result of her poor physical condition. And that closes the sad chapters in Paloma's life. From now on, Paloma's life will be filled with love, happiness, soft beds, toys, treats and a forever family who will cherish her. Paloma is a laid back, low maintenance, quiet lady who is happy with a few walks a day. She would be happy as a solo doggy, or with a doggy sibling her size or larger. Paloma
mostly likes to cuddle on the couch and nap. You will not regret making this sweet girl a part of your family!

animal.description:
Sofia is a 1 1/2-year old female German Shepherd dog that was surrendered to Animal Control Services, along with her 3-month old puppy. She didnt have the best start in life--she was scared and shut down when she entered our program. But dogs have a way of moving forward and not looking back. She is now safe and our organization will ensure that she will have a positive future.

Sophia is relaxed and comfy in her foster home and loves human attention. She has a good appetite and has gained weight! She was a nurturing mother to her puppy that has since been adopted. She is just a bit older than a puppy herself.

She is hesitant about walking on a leash, but is improving every day.

Sofia needs a quiet adult home with an adopter who can build her confidence. Sophia is a little hesitant around men so were looking for the perfect match in an environment that will lead to a successful transition, and not have great potential for setbacks. Do you have another dog? Sophia loves other dogs, and we have seen a companion dog bring her out of her shell! 

Although Sofia is very well behaved, an adopter should provide her with the basic obedience training (based upon positive reinforcement) that any young dog requires. It will be necessary for an adopter to have recent experience in raising a shy GSD or other large breed working dog. 

Shes waiting just for you!

animal.description:
At the end of her second year with us, Fluffy was adopted into a home.  Unfortunately, she wasn't happy and they decided to bring her back.  Fluffy is a 4 year old female Lab mix that has not had a good chance at a real life yet.  Prior to coming to us, she was housed in an outdoor kennel until her owner decided to move and leave her behind with several other dogs.  Fluffy went the Dog Warden's office, and then came to us for adoption.  She needs a fenced yard and someone the will give her the time to decompress.  She does not care for men, so if she lives with a man, they will need to understand that they should just ignore her until she comes around on her own terms.  And the whole process might take months.  Fluffy loves to sit in the yard and relax and watch the world go by, and if that's what she wants, that's what she should be allowed to do.  Someone just needs to give her a chance.

If you would like an application go to our website and download one and email it back as a Word or PDF document.

This dog's adoption fee is $190. That fee includes spaying/ neutering, microchipping, deworming and vaccinations. If you would like an adoption application, please send an email message to adoptprebleco@yahoo.com

animal.description:
This little guy is quite a character. Peppe is 2 years old and weighs about 12 lbs. He was pulled from Fulton county animal control where he was surrendered in August of 2016 because of financial reasons. Then he got adopted 2 months later and returned 2 weeks later because he snapped at his new owner protecting his food. They were warned about his food aggression. The same happened again after his second adoption where he was returned after only 4 days. He was scheduled to be euthanized that day when he got returned again but not on our watch. We just happened to be there and took him to give him another chance of life. 
He is a sweet little cuddle bug and loves attention and is very playful He is very easy going and and most of the time sweet as he can be, but he does have his little episodes where he will snap. A few times it happened when he was sleeping next to a person on the couch and then out of a sudden woke up and snapped to the person next to him, so we were told. We think he just need an alpha person when it comes to him protecting his food or toys.  Peppe loves to ride in the car and go places. He is also off leash obedient. animal.description:
Baby has been going through Hell back and forth. She was abandoned, living all by herself in an empty house for 3 months.
The neighbor finally found out once they saw her walking through the yard nothing but skin and bones. Police and Animal Control was contacted, but nobody was willing to help.
So they neighbor started feeding her and put a bucket of food and water every day over the fence.
Finally somebody reached out to us and we took on this task. 1 person went over there multiple times a day and just sat in the yard without saying a word. Just building trust with presence. She started to come closer and ate out of the hand but didn't want to get touched. Eventually we put out a humane trap and after a few days we were able to trap her in it. The morning we finally captured her, she greeted us with a wagging tail and did a 180 personality change. She let us put her on a leash and jumped right in the car and was like a different dog.  She doe snot like cats but She is great with other dogs and loves kids all age. She does better in a low traffic home as she is very protective of her family. She will bark at strangers and can sound quite intimidating. Someone who lives alone or a family who doesn't a have many many visitor would be best. She is a doll and these pictures doesn't even show her real beauty. She  deserves a great home. She is housebroken, non destructive, has the softest coat ever and once she trust you just a cuddle bug. For some reason Baby has been terribly over looked and has been with us for 3 years. She barely get applications which is unbelievable because she is not only stunning but also the sweetest girl you have ever met.
She has some food allergies and can only have poultry and grain fee foods but otherwise she is happy and healthy.

She is great with other dogs but would also be ok as the only dog since she is not a big player at all. If she can pick over dog companionship or humans, she will pick her human every time. All she wants is to please and be with you .
She just needs a chance to show that for the past years someone was missing out on the perfect dog.. 
She is about 5 years old and weighs between 45 and 50 lbs,

UPDATE 7/25/20 Baby just recently developed a food allergy to grains and poultry. She can only have foods and treats without those ingredients.

If you would like to meet Baby please send us a message in order to receive an application. We are only able to meet with are approved applicants since we do not have a shelter available to the public.

Baby's adoption fee is $ 250 which includes all vaccines, heartworm test, spay and micro chip.

animal.description:
0520218 - Maise is an incredible companion and LOVES people of all ages and sizes. Her whole butt wags every time a person is near! She is a 3 year old pitbull/cane corso mix and still has lots of puppy energy. She would do best in a household that is physically active and can get her out for daily exercise, not just letting her out in a yard although she would also love a yard and is great at fetch. She will need someone willing to work with her and her anxiety around dogs outside of her home, she is strong and will pull. We recommend any adopter plan on hiring a trainer (we have some we can recommend!) for a few sessions to make sure you start out on the right foot. Maise does likes other dogs she just needs a slow introduction, a nice leash walk first has worked well prior to introducing them in the house. She loves her doggie foster siblings. She will also need a yard with a 6ft fence. Maise loves kids and has been real good while meeting them. Maise is smart and eager to please so with a little love and patience she will be a wonderful companion. She loves to cuddle and thinks she is a lap dog. She will drench you in kisses and beg for snuggles any time of the day.

Because of Maise's breeds she can not be adopted to anyone living in a city with breed restrictions and you must own your home.

My story is short and sweet. I’m looking for my forever home –short and sweet and to the point! I know, I know – I’m incredibly handsome. :)

My brothers (Beck and Gordon) and I have lived outside all our lives and have not had any contact with people (or other dogs). I am the most fearful and untrusting of the 3 of us – but I’m getting better every day. Baby steps! Can you love me and help me learn to trust?

I’ve just joined the wonderful Brittanys at BRIT and am looking for a foster home so BRIT can report back with my great personality traits. I came from a nice place but had absolutely NO socialization. I’m inexperienced in life and very cautious. I need a home with another Brittany who can show me how to be a Brittany – I honestly don’t have a clue.

Please check back for updates on me at www.brittanyrescueintexas.org


Cyrus is up to date on shots, neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative and on preventative. He’s looking for a foster or even better a forever home. He needs a family that is very patient, supportive and consistent to help him gain the confidence he needs to be the best Brittany he can be.

Jerry Brown is seeking a young family with a fenced yard who will love him and can handle his boundless energy and toy fetish.  Speaking of toys, he will carry them all around the house until someone agrees to play tug-a-war with him.  
Jerry Brown is the best car rider!  He loves to go bye bye and explore new places.   
JB is leash trained, house trained, neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped 
Jerry is quite a large dog and would not be a good fit for small children or elderly owners.  Sometimes his prey drive will kick in and  it takes a strong hand to hold him if he sees a ground hog, opossum, or a squirrel!   

If you think this handsome man may be your soulmate please copy and paste the link for an application

https://forms.gle/i6vCT6447Eew8NCg9

animal.description: ***ZANE WILL NOT BE AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION UNTIL AT LEAST 11/1/20***In a joint rescue effort with Muttley Crue Rescue, we were able to pull three Boxers from the shelter in Zanesville, OH. The two boys came to us with the female named Jenga going to Muttley Crue. Zane arrived at his Illinois foster home yesterday after going straight to the vet in Dayton from the shelter. He is completely vetted, including having the cyst removed from his head, having a bad tooth removed, neutered and microchipped. He is good with other dogs. Zane was fear reactive in the kennel at the shelter, mostly to one of the male wardens. He was reactive in the crate on transport out of the shelter but on all transport after that he rode tethered and was amazing. He will crate right up, he just seems to be afraid of what might happen when crated. His foster dad will update us on how that is going. He is a big boy and is definitely a ladies man...he took right to his foster dad but may have some fear issues when meeting new men, we will work on and update on that, as well. 9/5: Zane's foster dad is continuing to work with him on his fear issues. He will not be available for adoption until at least 11/1/20. Please check back in on him soon!

animal.description:
Chucky is a 58lb, 12 year old, hamburger loving senior pit mix boy. He is an avid fan of walks and playtime, and needs no coaxing to enjoy life! He has much left in him! When he sees the leash, Chucky will perk up and wag his tail with joy at the prospect of exploring the neighborhood. Have a toy? Chucky loves balls and squeaky toys! Ready to roll around in the grass or toss them in the air. 

All in all, Chucky is an easygoing dog. He is people friendly, affectionate, a lover of kisses, and playful. Furthermore, Chucky is dog friendly (cats unknown), house trained, crate trained, and trustworthy when home alone.

Chucky isn't usually bothered if his food or treats are touched or taken away. However, he will gently grab the person's hand with his mouth and move it away so that his food isn't taken away.

Please note that Chucky is reported to be fearful of children so he needs to be in an adult only home. 

If you're looking for a medium-energy dog who is equally happy sitting next to you on the couch as going for a pleasant stroll, Chucky could be the one for you!

If interested in adopting or fostering, email us at twentypawsrescue@gmail.com or info@twentypawsrescue.com. Please note that due to an email glitch, sometimes emails get lost. We respond to all emails! So, If you do not hear from us, please follow up!

AVAILABLE THROUGH ANIMAL ALLIANCE

Isosceles is an 8 year old tripod of a Rat Terrier.  He's currently on a diet in a foster home with five other dogs ranging from 12-50lbs and many cats.  If picked up the "wrong way" (a way that bothers his stump), he can be nippy so small children are not recommended.  Since losing weight, his mobility has improved immensely, and he is incredibly fast.  He is crate-trained.  He does like to run, so a fenced-in backyard is ideal.  He does like to bark at noises outside so apartments are not a good idea.  He loves hunting for duck eggs in his foster's backyard and loves car rides.  He is wary of strangers but very loving and sweet to his owner.  If you are interested in this little butterball, please fill out an adoption application for him at animalalliancenj.org.  He is currently being fostered in Warren County.

animal.description: Princess Buttercup is waiting for her forever home!She cannot stay in the kennel as being around other dogs stresses her out. In her foster home she's made so much progress and has proven herself to be an amazing companion! She's a total sweetheart with a fun and quirky personality. She's never met a person she doesn't like and does well with everyone - but also keeps a respectful distance from those who don't want to be her friend. If she had her way, you'd start working from home so she'll never have to be without you - she can be anxious when left alone in a new environment, but settles in once she feels safe and secure. Mornings are peak snuggle-time for Princess Buttercup; if you're not a morning person already, you will be once you make her part of your family. Don't worry though, she'll never run out of cuddles or affection for the people around her. She's generally a well-behaved girl with just enough of a naughty streak to keep you on your toes (i.e be careful about leaving food around, even if you think it's beyond her reach). She's fully house trained and continues to work on her crate skills. Grooming is generally hassle-free is you ask her nicely and make sure there's a treat in it for her. She does well in public, and while she's definitely not a dog-person, she is pretty easy on walks and doesn't bark at anyone. If you think you're ready to add additional cuddles, laughter, and love to your life, Princess Buttercup is the right dog for you. If you are interested in meeting Princess Buttercup, go to la.bestfriends.org/adopt and fill out our Dog Adoption Survey and our team will reach out to you!

animal.description: Cherish is an absolute angel, complete with a halo! This adorable little gal never turns down a moment to "smize" for the camera! She loves that her glam squad at Best Friends Los Angeles acquiesces to her requests for photo shoots, complete with wings of her own a la Victoria's Secret Angel. Blind and diabetic, the shelter environment is no place for this 5-year-old to thrive. Cherish has spent time in a foster home and settled in quickly. Despite her visual impairment, she acclimates quickly to her surroundings and is a calm, sweet, and curious girl. Cherish is house trained (with easy, regular access to the outdoors) and very easy-going. Cherish loves people and is curious about other dogs. She needs a slow introduction, supervision, and management around other canines. She is a bit pushy and nervous, but desperately wants to be friends - meaning that other dogs need to be understanding and patient with her. Cherish would do best in a home with no cats.When you adopt Cherish you will also receive a gift from 1-800-PetMeds to welcome her home. If you are interested in meeting Cherish, go to la.bestfriends.org/adopt and fill out our Dog Adoption Survey and our team will reach out to you!

animal.description:
Female Plott Hound-Mountain Cur Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 07/02/2018

Weight: 60.5 lbs

Children: Yes 

Dogs: No 

Cats: No 

Farm Animals: No 

Bird and small animals: No 


Leela is an energetic, playful girl who would love to finally have a family of her own. Sadly she has been in shelters since mid-2019 and came to us from a municipal shelter in West Virginia. When she was young, she was hit by a car, causing permanent damage to her left eye but it causes her no pain and does not require any current treatment or medication. You would never know she is practically blind in her left eye because it doesn't slow her down one bit. In fact, she's super aware of her surroundings and has a strong prey instinct so she can't go to a home with farm animals, cats, birds or any similar species.

Leela absolutely loves to play fetch and is amazing at it. If fetch was a competitive sport, you would want her on your team! She is so smart and just wants to be around people all of the time. Do you want a dog to go with you on a hike during the day then return home to just Netflix and chill with you on the couch for the evening? Then Leela's your girl! She will be by your side in so many fun activities from playing in the water to hiking up a mountain; she is the sporty sidekick you've been looking for. Need some cuddle time? She will snuggle up right beside you.

Leela just wants to be your best friend and aims to please the people in her life. Her reaction to seeing you when you walk through the door will make you feel like the most loved person in the world. 

Is Leela the one you've been waiting for?

animal.description:
Meet Jedi!! He came in as a stray on 5/21/20. He is about 2 years old. Jedi was tested with food for aggression and passed. He was also tested with dogs (male and female), He did great with females but only ok with some males so he may need a home without males. He does need a home without cats! Jedi is neutered and does have his rabies vaccination.

Jedi is located at the Manci Prison Program for training, he is not at our shelter. If you would like to set up a time to meet him you will need to send an email to: Christina.thomas@odrc.state.oh.us

UPDATE FROM PRISON PROGRAM:
Jedi has become like any normal dog, his progress was extremely fast, he came to us fully trained in his basic commands. He's just about ready for adoption. The only problems he has are with people that he's not familiar with reaching for his muzzle, due to his teeth being damaged. He has no toy-food or dog aggression. But he has to be introduced in the right way to certain dogs.

For an adoption application you can request one via richlandcountypets@yahoo.com

animal.description:
Follow us on Facebook for updated photos and more information on our adoptable pets!

This sweet girl was a stray, she was scared, shy and lost. A perfect example of how a dog acts when they are abandoned by their owner. 

Meet Millie, a 1 year old lab and pit mix. Millie knows how to sit, shake, stay and lay. Millie specifically loves squeaker toys, she knows where her toy box is and is not shy to entertain herself with toys provided. Although she hasn’t mastered picking up after herself! ? Millie also loves a good bone, and is kind enough to allow you to take it from her whenever you wish. Millie is both potty trained and crate trained. She knows the “kennel up” command, making the crating process an ease. She has proven to be well-behaved at nighttime, and is allowed to sleep outside of the crate. Millie loves people and wants to be close to her “person”. She loves to snuggle but will be respectful of boundaries that are set. 

Millie is smart, quick to learn and wants to please; she just needs someone who will set the standards. She needs to be an only dog. Millie is not good with cats. Millie will need a home with a fenced in yard. Mille would do great in a home no apartments. Millie does amazing with respectful children. 

Mille is vaccinated for rabies, distemper, and bordatella. She is spayed and microchipped. Millie’s adoption fee is $400 plus WI state tax!

Fill out an application at www.luckypawsmidwest.org once your application is approved we will set up a meet and greet. 

Lucky Paws Midwest is licensed and inspected by the State of Wisconsin: 402655-DS

Age: 7 yrs
Weight: 70 lbs
Reported good with kids 12+

Jordan is a calm quiet lady who is happiest just relaxing with the family. She is looking for a peaceful life where she can settle back and take walks with plenty of time to stop and smell nature. Jordan loves to use her nose whether it is pushing a toy, looking for treats, or just investigating during her daily walk. 

Jordan is a wonderful work-from-home partner if you dont mind a little snoring. She quickly adapts to a routine and doesnt ask for much during the day. Jordan is house and crate trained and loves to ride in the car. She does not pull on the leash but will stop and let you know which way she wants to walk.

Jordan is cautious and she can become easily startled which causes her to retreat to her bed. She could use help building confidence and her foster family is working with her, but she will need consistency and patience from her adopter to continue their efforts.

She is a laid-back girl looking for a calm household. If you give Jordan time to warm up, she provides nonstop love. Do you have a warm spot in your heart and home for this beautiful and serene lass?

You can apply to adopt Jordan at https://www.mostlymuttz.org/adoption-application/.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Lauren for more information about this pet.Paw Up! Date: Peanut aka Blackie is Back Home!

Our sweet lil Peanut is back with his foster...sadly, his rear leg was in such bad shape the best option for him was amputation. Peanut's leg was horribly infected (we ran a culture to make sure we have him on the right antibiotics) and his bone was compromised from it. He is home resting, already ate a good dinner and in a couple of weeks will be out running and playing. Tonight it is all about resting and getting his strength back after all he has been through. Thank you to everyone who donated towards his surgery and care. Peanut is a sweet baby and we are grateful we are able to help him with your support!!

In the Beginning:

Puppy Blackie aka Peanut Needs US!!!

When we saw the picture of a baby laying on the side of a rode with a huge gash on his leg our hearts sank. We had no idea where he was, but offered to help...he was in Tijuana! We normally can't help the dogs of TJ because we don't have any volunteers or resources there. When a local rescuer offered to help and go pick him up we agreed to rescue him. A Good Samaritan saw it happen, a truck who could have avoided him, decided not too...we feared there was a break and oh boy is there. Peanut was stabilized in TJ and made his way to us this weekend. He is in a foster home awaiting surgery with an orthopedic surgeon to repair that break! Peanut is the sweetest little man, he is about 5 months old and maybe 15 pounds. We need your help to help Peanut! We know Covid is taking its toll, but we couldn't leave him to die on the side of a road in Tijuana!

Ways to Donate:
Facebook: via the button on the post
Venmo: @labradorsandfriends
PayPal: labradorsandfriends@yahoo.com
Website: www.labradorsandfriends.org
Check/Cash in the mail: Labradors and Friends - 2307 Fenton Parkway #107-160, San Diego, CA 92108
Tax ID#32-0195297

animal.description:
3.5 year old female spayed black/brindle Mastiff/Lab mix, 65 lbs.

Where did you get this dog?: Hearts for Paws Rescue on January 1, 2018.

Why is the dog being given up?: She was spooked my a biker and bite them resulting in her being deemed a potentially dangerous dog in El Dorado County. She is super sweet and we wish we could keep her but we are being kicked out of our house because of it and are having a hard time finding a new rental.

Check the words that best describe your dog: PROTECTIVE, ACTIVE, PLAYFUL, NERVOUS, SMART, AFFECTIONATE

Is the dog currently on vaccinations?: Yes

Is your dog housebroken?: Yes

Are there any behavior problems?: Yes

If yes, please describe in as much detail as possible: Reaction to bikes and offleash dogs that spook her. 

Does the dog get along with:: Dog-Friendly. Ella does best when she lives with another dog. She has a lot of dog friends. She isn't good at first impressions so she doesn't go to the dog park. She is leash reactive only if an off leash dog approaches her without the "proper" introduction.

Does your dog have handling sensitivities? How is your dog meeting strangers?: She can be timid when you approach her from behind. She doesn't like to be picked up. She is timid at first but overall fine.

Does the dog like children?: Yes

Are there children in the home?: No

Any specific feeding instructions you would care to share with your dogs new owner?: None. She is not food aggressive. She does wait for her "okay" to start eating.

Where does the dog sleep?: In the bed, on the floor next to the bed, or in her crate.

Is the dog allowed on your furniture?: Yes

Is the dog crate trained?: Yes

Where do you keep your dog: When we aren't home we keep her in the crate: She is free to go wherever she wants, she mostly hangs out on the couch with us, in her crate, or in our bed.

How does the dog react to being left alone?: She is fine with it.

Please list any particular fears your dog has.: Bikes, motorcycles, off leash strange dogs.

Desrcibe any training the dog has, tricks it knows, and any experience with a trainer.: She had private trainings with Sandy Matthieson and also group trainings with her. She is good at sit, stay, leave it, drop it, look, lay down, load up, touch, shake, high five, etc.

Does the dog have any known health problems?: No

Does the dog like riding in the car?: Yes

What does the dog like?: String cheese, putting her collar on, belly rubs, walks, tug toys

What does the dog dislike?: Being picked up or startled 

Is there anything else you can share that is special, unusual, or endearing about your dog that will help the new owners?: She is the biggest cuddle bug! Also, any time you reach down to pet her and she is comfortable around you, she will just immediately lay down for belly rubs.

Are there any things you think a new owner needs to know?: You have to introduce her to dogs in the right way! We have told many dog sitters this and they don't believe us. Then the dog introduction goes poorly. 

Please describe a typical day for your dog during the workweek (what time wake up, when eat, how many walks a day, where to -- dog parks, trails, neighborhoods, runs, etc), how long left home alone, what time to bed?: 6 am - wake up hang out with dad
7 am - go back to bed to cuddle with mom
9 am - get out of bed, go outside, and eat breakfast
10 am - 30 min walk
11 am - home along in crate
12 pm - go outside then home alone again
5 pm - 30 min walk
6 pm - dinner then cuddles, usually refuses to go outside again for the rest of the night

She only reacts to bikes when they sneak up on her (if she seems them coming, she is fine), motorcycles and off leash dogs who approach her. She has to meet other dogs by walking on leash with them parallel for approximately 5 min and then she is ready to be best friends. (Puppies don't require any warming up.) She is crate trained and loves it. She also knows sit, stay, lay down, come, look, touch, drop it, leave it. She is super smart and picks up new commands quickly.

APPLY at heartsforpawsrescue.com/adopt

Name: Tabitha
Breed: Lab Mix
Approximate Age: 1y 3m, DOB Oct 1, 2019
Approximate Weight: 36 lbs.
Location: Delaware
Tabitha was found running along a road in NC with her 2 siblings. She is a very sweet pup but is fearful. She needs a home that will have patience with her. Someone who will give her room and time to warm up at her own pace. She will NEED another dog in the house and a fenced in yard.  Tabitha is house trained, and crate trained. Her behavior is outstanding at her foster home, she has never damaged or chewed anything and gets along great with her foster siblings.  She knows the following commands: Crate Up, Go Lay down, Wait, Let's go out to Potty, Time to eat, Time for a treat.  Tabitha loves her crate; she will require a crate in her new home to adjust She will be a great dog if given lots of love and patience to give her time to be the great dog she can be. We also feel that children older than 10 would be best for her.
Tabitha is spayed, microchipped and up to date on her vaccines. 

If you are interested in Tabitha, please fill out our application which can be found on our web site www.itavar.com. Once we get your application, we will call you to set up a meet n greet.

You can also see more pictures on our Facebook page, https://www.facebook.com/ITAVAR/

animal.description:
Cher is around 10 years old and 8 pounds. She is a sweet older girl, shy around people at first and loves other dogs. She is heart worm positive and our rescue will treat.

All our pets are spayed or neutered, vaccinated including rabies, given de-wormer, heartworm negative or being treated with the slow kill method approved by our veterinarian, on prevention, on flea/tick prevention, most are house trained. The majority but not all of our pets require a fence. Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered. We adopt within 300 miles of New Orleans/Baton Rouge, La and we do not ship or transport--Adoption fee $200. Email us at creolepoodlerescue@yahoo.com to get an adoption application. Complete an adoption form and email it back to us (we do not have a FAX) if interested in adopting and providing a loving home for this pet.  If you can't email it to us, you can mail it to P.O. Box 2333, Gonzales, La 70707, but this will slow the process down.

When you request an adoption application, we will also send you our guidelines to read - many questions you may have are answered there.  All of our pets are in private foster homes. We require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meeting for any of our pets. Everything we know at this time about this pet is posted.IF YOU SEE THIS PET POSTED ON OUR ADOPTABLE PETS PAGE, THIS PET IS AVAILABLE. WE UPDATE OUR ADOPTABLE PETS SEVERAL TIMES DAILY.  IF THE WORD PENDING IS NEXT TO THE NAME, THE PET HAS AN APPROVED ADOPTER COMING TO MEET AND PROBABLY ADOPT HIM OR HER.  We reserve the right to refuse adoption for any reason.

We are all VOLUNTEERS and have full time jobs, families, pets of our own to care for - we do the best that we can to get back to you in a timely manner.  Please realize that turning in an application today will not mean that you adopt a poodle tomorrow.  We believe in taking the time to go through our thorough process to try to match the dog with the family.

Meet Sarah Talbot. She is an adorable female dachshund (doxie) mix. She is brown / brindle in color and petite and cute. She is about 4 years old and weighs about 13 lbs. She is sweet and friendly with people and other dogs. She was accepted into the rescue w her friend Sawyer (male doxie mix). She has been vaccinated and dewormed and is heartworm positive. Our Adoption Area - WAGS RESCUE is based in BUCKS COUNTY. Therefore, a majority of our volunteers live in the Bucks County area. WAGS will consider adoption applications for people living in the BUCKS and MONTGOMERY areas. On a case by case basis (depending on distance and availability of our volunteers to do a home visit), we may consider applications in the PHILADELPHIA area as well as parts of CHESTER county.

Due to a higher than normal volume of applications, we will not be doing any adoptions outside a 50-mile radius from Horsham Veterinary Hospital.

Thank you for your understanding.

Please call Colleen @ 267-238-7892 or Susan @ 267-312-3372. To begin the adoption process please, please fill out our online application. Go to wagsrescue.com and click on adoption form. After you complete the application, you will be taken to PayPal so you can submit the $25.00 application fee. Thank you!

animal.description:
Please contact us directly at Deethenetworker@gmail.com for more information 

Los Angeles - CA  5 year old black Great Dane male. Goblin was brought down from the Pacific Northwest from a difficult family situation where he was in the middle of somewhere short of domestic violence, but certainly verbal arguments. Something a protective Great Dane would have trouble navigating through. He was sent back to his first home but unable to live with his brother as both boys were now adults and dominant. There were terrible dog fights and Goblin has since become extremely dog reactive.  Goblin has grown up with children and farm animals. It is heartbreaking that he is now reactive to both male and female dogs. Could it be fixed? Maybe with proper training. But the risk of hurting another dog is great. I would not nor do I expect anyone else to take on that risk. We are looking for a one dog home with a secure yard and lifestyle that keeps Goblin safely at home. Trips to veterinary clinic must include a proper muzzle. I will provide a correctly sized Baskerville to adopter. Goblin is not for every home, but I believe the right family is out there. I will consider out of area adoption with the proper references including a verifiable veterinary history and home check by local animal rescue or professionals. Inside of home can be done via video considering the current COVID-19 circumstances we live in today.  This is an absolutely wonderful, loving, friendly dog to all humans.  Plays nicely with his toys, takes treats gently.  He has a good 'sit'.  But will pull on the leash when he sees other dogs.  Some behavioral modification and training is a must.

Contact us directly at Deethehetworker@gmail.com

animal.description:
This special old guy is Spark, and he has been waiting for a very long time for a forever home of his own. 

Spark is about 11 years old, and is an extremely handsome old guy. He’s part Blue Heeler and part German Shepherd, and he definitely got the good looks and brains from both breeds. He takes a while to warm up to new people, but once he trusts you he will show you all of the training he has under his belt! For the people he has formed a bond with he will wait at gates/doors and does not  pass through until you say 'okay'. He will sit for treats and he will be super easy to walk. He will be calm around traffic and will ride nicely in the car. He is really a great guy in so many ways.

Spark will need to be with someone who will introduce him to new people thoughtfully and carefully. He will also need to be with someone who is understanding of his old dog crotchety nature at times. He would love to live on a farm with someone who appreciates him for who he is and doesn’t push him into uncomfortable situations. 

Spark has lived with dogs before, but not children. We feel as if he’d do best in a mature household with someone who has previous dog experience. 

Spark is a gem, and needs someone who can pull the best out of him and give him a comfortable loving home for his golden years. We are partnering with the Stray Hearts Animal Shelter in Taos New Mexico to find Spark a forever home. Please help us spread the word for this amazing old guy!!!


PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior pets have a history of being kept up to date on vaccines, annual exams and recommended bloodwork. We also do home checks to make sure that your home environment meets the needs of the particular dog you are interested in.

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at http://olddogsnewdigs.com/form-adoption.html.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

If you would like to take me home please complete a Pet Adoption Application

Male , 43 lb. Shepherd Mix
PERMANENT FOSTER NEEDED!!!

Below we have indicated what was told to us upon intake. Once we assess the dog we will update the following:

Background: Humane court case.
Personality: Prefers slow intros. True shepherd will bond with handlers. Fearful at first introductions. No bite history.
Cats: No
Dogs: No
Kids: No adult only home
Energy Level: High
Housebroken: Yes
Crate Trained: Yes
Prey Drive For Wildlife (no invisible fence if high): High
Fence Required: No
Best Home For This Pet: Shepard experience with fearful dogs.Low traffic home away from major roads.

We do our best to get to know each and every dog at our camp. Their personalities emerge after being with us for a bit and sometimes change. The personality and other information included in the above description is based on what we know currently in the shelter environment. All dogs are up to date on vaccines (Distemper, Rabies, Bordetella), microchipped, spayed/neutered and receive worming, flea & tick medication before they are adopted out. Please note there are some exceptions depending on the condition of the dog. If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application at https://www.camppapillon.org/dog-application.

Once your dog is in your home, they will adjust and relax and could become more playful or show more personality traits as they begin to open up. Once adopted, please allow your dog time to decompress and relax in a stable home environment

animal.description:
Ella is a lovely gal and absolutely stunning! 2 years old, weighing around 60lbs. She is good with other dogs similar to her size, however, she would be excellent as the only dog too as she prefers the company of people. She tends to resource guards with other dogs, easy to manage though. We feed everyone separately in crates and chews and toys are reserved for crate time. NO CATS or other small animals please, she is way too interested. Ella is good with considerate people in general, however, we prefer to place her in a adult only home or a home with teenagers due to her size, strength  & energy. She is house/crate trained. Needs a little leash work, but responds well to positive methods of training. This gal would thrive best in a active home with plenty of outdoor adventures! Someone is going to adopt a fantastic girl!

animal.description:
Kiera is a stunning, 4 year old German Shepherd. She found herself in our care after her owner passed away & the extended family could not care for her. 

Kiera is a wonderful dog, but due to poor socialization in her former home she is very fearful in new situations. Kiera needs a home that can allow her the space to decompress and adjust, as well as additional training to continue her rehab. 

Kiera would thrive in an adult only home, outside of the city. She lived in a private home with a yard, and is finding the city too stimulating and unpredictable for her liking. 

She has been exposed to cats, and has done well around them. We think she could potentially live with other small dogs. Her behavior around larger dogs is unknown at this time.

Kiera is housebroken, and knows a few commands. She is not affectionate with strangers until she feels safe, so it does take her time to warm up. Once she does, she bonds fiercely to her people and can get protective. We are trying to work through this but she will need an experienced handler to continue. 


If you are interested in adopting, Please Read Below.

We do not have a public shelter, all of our dogs are in private foster homes. Applications are processed in the order in which they are received. You can email adopt.truenorthrescue@gmail.com for more information.

Think this dog is the one for you? Apply today at www.truenorthrescue.org.

You may read more about our adoption policies and procedures at www.truenorthrescue.org. Please submit a complete application on our website - meet and greets are only scheduled with approved applicants. Please be sure to answer every question as thoughtfully as you can, this will help your chances. Incomplete applications will not be reviewed, and we unfortunately can not contact all applicants to inquire about missing information.

Do not email through Petfinder because we won't be able to answer. Please email adopt.truenorthrescue@gmail.com to check on the status of your application. All applications can take anywhere from 24-72 hours to be processed and only approved applicants will be contacted.

If a dog is listed here on Petfinder, they are still available. Please don't email just to ask if they're available - they are! With the high volume of emails we receive daily, it is not guaranteed that we can reply to every inquiry. As a fully volunteer run rescue, we make every effort to reply in a timely fashion, but please allow 24-48 hours for a response.

We strive to have accurate and up to date bios, and regularly check in with our fosters to ensure we are providing the most relevant information. If there is no mention of a health or behavioral concern, then it means we have not been informed of one!

animal.description:
Hi, I’m TT, and I’m Tiny, Terrific, and Too Cute! That’s three “T’s”? No worries, with a dog like me you can expect all kinds of extras--extra cuddles, extra snuggles, and extra love! I’m one year old, weigh 6.5 pounds, and am spayed, fully vetted, vaccinated, and on heartworm preventative. That means I’m ready for my forever home, maybe with you!

I’m just a young pup, which means I’m Tireless! I love to run and play in the yard with my foster siblings and chase the cats if they let me. Toys are so much fun, but I share very well with other dogs and get along with dogs of all sizes. I'll definitely need some dog siblings in my new home, as well as a fenced yard we can all play in together! I’m also Tender-hearted! I love to cuddle with my foster moms in a cozy blanket.

Despite my small size and young age, I’m Tough and Tenacious! I have a special medical condition called megaesophagus. That means my esophagus, the tube that carries food and water from my mouth to my stomach, gets larger and loses its ability to do its job. Left on its own, food and water slosh around in my esophagus and can’t make it to my stomach, which means I could choke. Don’t worry though! I have my own special highchair to keep me upright while I’m eating, allowing gravity to help move my food to the right location (if you adopt me, my chair comes along too!). My foster moms would be happy to teach you how to feed me and keep me safe. 

Because of my condition, I need a mom or dad who has experience with dogs--even better if they have experience with special needs dogs like me! I would love a home with another dog to play with, but I can’t be with younger children who don’t understand how dangerous it is to give me extra food or treats. I’ll need to stay in my crate, which I love, while you’re away to be sure I don’t get into any mischief. 

I don’t let my medical condition define me, and I hope you won’t either. I will be your Trusted and True companion if you will give me the care I need. I promise we will be even more Tremendous Together!

If you would like to learn more about megaesophagus, please visit https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/megaesophagus.

If you are interested in adopting TT, please DO NOT SEND A MESSAGE TO OUR RESCUE GROUP.  We are too busy placing dogs in great homes to answer messages and inquiries through the listing site.  

PLEASE GO TO THE LINK BELOW TO COMPLETE AN ADOPTION APPLICATION.
 
www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application
 
CRT requires an approved adoption application and a home visit for all adoption applicants.  CRT transports to OH, KY, IL, MI, MN, WI.

animal.description:
Meet Jackson!

Hi, my name is Jackson! I'm a four-year-old German Shepherd/Coonhound mix! I am about 85lbs, my birthday is February 9th, and I have the most loving personality! I'm so willing to please and know a lot of tricks, from sit, stay, and paw to just walking properly on the leash. I do however have some special requests...

I have severe separation anxiety. Please don't leave me out all alone or I might eat some furniture legs or gnaw on some shoes because I get so upset about you leaving! I am crate trained. My crate is my safe place. I need a home where someone is home all day, or with a couple that works alternate shifts.  I also need to be the only animal in the home because I love to chase cats and don't always pick up on doggy social cues. (Some would call me overly friendly.) I am used to going to doggy daycare and I do play well with other dogs when I'm supervised, but my bigger size and super long tail sometimes cause problems. I love kids and I would love some kids to play with me in a huge backyard (kids have to be over 9 years of age per Animal Alliance policy). It doesn't need to be fenced in, as my recall is very good! I love to go hiking, that's my favorite activity! It's even better if there's water involved because I love swimming and playing fetch!

Here's where my issues lay:

I do have an eating disorder where I don't always like to eat my food. I have been on over 50 kibbles and raw feed, and I stop eating every time. I often go days refusing to eat, so I need a financially stable home that can afford to either put me back on a true and proper raw feed diet or someone that will cook meals for me .(I can not go to a home that will provide me  kibble, I just hate kibble so much!) I can not stress this enough, this is the diet I need to be on! Please do not apply if you can't meet my dietary needs. My mom is willing to give you the feeding guidelines to get us started. The average cost of my raw feed is 90$ a week. The vet has cleared me, this isn't from anything medically wrong with me aside from possible allergies, which is why this diet is so important. I do have to also take a Tums every morning and night as I also suffer from doggy acid reflux. My mom is a groomer and bathes me every 2 weeks with a medicated shampoo to soothe my skin. I am wonderful for baths and nail trims. (My mom will even still offer to groom me for free.) I need a secure home that can help me through my issues. Between my eating problems, fear of loud noises like fireworks, and separation anxiety, I could really used a skilled and patient hand to hold while we figure these things out.  Please don't let these issues scare you off. My mom loves me very much but sadly works long and hard hours Monday- Friday and can not financially afford my special diet. She truly wants what's best for me.

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

Noel was found laying in a field with a prolapsed colon. The poor girl was riddled with worms and had eaten a number of things that weren't actually food. After two major surgeries she's just like any normal dog, even if her colon is a little bit shorter now. She loves to explore and find new things to sniff (and try to eat). She loves other dogs, especially active dogs who like to wrestle. She's short in stature, but can regularly pin my own dog who is nearly twice her size. She's a chewer so it's a good idea to keep plenty of nyla bones, antlers, or other things that are safe to chew around the house. She cannot have rawhide or cloth toys of any kind as they are difficult to digest. She's a sucker for peanut butter and loves her Kong toys when filled with something she likes. Bananas are an acceptable substitute. 
She's friendly towards cats as all, but may try to play with them when she gets excited and most cats don't like to play the same way dogs too. She also gets overly excited when she sees a cat she hasn't met, particularly any strays or outdoor cats who may live in the area.
She's a really sweet and loving girl who needs to find her forever people. She's really shy at first, but warms up once she knows she can trust you.

animal.description: Puppies born under a shed, puppies dumped in the woods in a box, puppies thrown away at the rural dump in a remote county of Tennessee These are the stories we see unfolding every day. Puppies left to wonder alone, no food or water available and no one to care about them except the individuals who stumble upon them and cannot turn their backs. This our rescue story every day in Middle Tennessee. These little babies here in this picture were born under a shed and are not used to humans touching them and loving them until today when the shelter workers were able to crawl under the shed and pull them out. We have them now living in the light of day at the shelter and they are shy, scared and need some human love and touch. Critter Cavalry Rescue wants to help if only we had some foster families. We supply everything and all we need are the foster homes . Can you help!? They weigh less than 5 pounds and we want them to be kept together in groups of two or three puppies so they have the comfort of each other . How rewarding this will be for some family who wants to make a difference. Email us at ccrtennessee@gmail.comADOPTION FEE REQUIRED. Contact ccrtennessee@gmail.com.

animal.description:
JAKE MUST HAVE A GRASSY BACKYARD AND IS HEARING AND SIGHT IMPAIRED

Hello! My name is Jake and I'm 14-pound male Bichon Frise mix. My favorite thing to do is wander outside in my grassy backyard. My foster Mom insists that I really must have my own grassy backyard. All my doctors say I'm at least 12 years or older. I am a very mellow guy, that needs a calm, consistent home. I love long naps and then going out for some fresh air. I came to BROC as a surrender, my past family was unable to take care of me any longer. I have some arthritis in my rear legs, so walks are not my thing. I am vision impaired and I do need eye drops twice a day. I'm a sweet pup just looking for a forever loving home.

I have had a thorough health examination and dental cleaning. I'm microchipped and neutered. If you have room in your heart and home for a "special needs" guy like me, please complete an adoption application.

https://bichonrescueoc.org/adoption-application

In the struggle to cope with COVID-19 and its effects on our daily life, it has become necessary to suspend our customary adoption approval process. Scheduling your "Home Safety Evaluation" and a "Meet and Greet" presents a significant challenge. If you express an interest in adopting this Special Needs pup, we will make every effort to make that possible. You will be contacted to schedule a telephone interview and details of the current approval process will be explained.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Cooper! He is absolutely beautiful and huge! He weighs in at 150 lbs. but with very long legs he carries his weight well. He is not fat at all. He was born around October 2017. He is the biggest lap dog you will ever love!

Coop is sweet, happy, and full of love. He will steal your heart. He is so silly and always has a smile! He is a love bug who loves to give and receive hugs.

His favorite spot to be is laying at your feet as you enjoy your morning coffee. He loves sleeping on the floor or on his dog bed next to you at night, and lounging on a couch during the day. He has been an excellent co-worker while working at home through Covid, although he does snore a bit!

Cooper was born with luxating patellas (knees that sometimes move out of proper position) and weak hocks (ankles that have poor ligament support). SPIN worked with some of the best orthopedic vets in the metroplex and the decision was made that the best course of action for Cooper is to continue strengthening his leg muscles through exercise.

Cooper loves to walk, how far and how fast depends on how his legs are feeling. You will need to watch him, and you will be able to tell when he is getting tired.

He has recovered so thoroughly during his stay with us, you'd never know that he has a bad backend. His legs have gotten stronger from playing with the other dogs in his foster home.

Cooper will need to stay on carprofen/Rimadyl, glucosamine/Cosequin to support his continued improvement. He loves his pills when they're wrapped in Velveeta cheese! He loves anything wrapped in Velveeta!

Coopie loves playing with doggy friends. He would do well in a home with other dogs. He would also do well as an only dog with occasional play dates or doggy day care. Having his human at home a lot would be his preference. In fact, Cooper will welcome you home with exuberance any time you leave even if it's just a short trip to the grocery store. You will feel like a celebrity every time you come home!

Cooper is very smart and learns quickly. He is wonderful on leash. He is house trained and pet door trained. He is a Pyrfect gentleman while being bathed. If he must be contained for some reason, he will tolerate being in a large exercise pen. But it's really not necessary to contain him.

Cooper is not a fan of cats, even when they're only on tv!

He is a wonderful travel companion. On the way to his adventure, he is smiley and active in the car, watching everything go past. He sleeps quietly the whole way home.

His new family needs to be diligent about keeping him active and keeping his hind muscles strong so he can continue to adequately support his imperfect legs.

Cooper is the absolute most loving dog who will bring so much happiness to his forever family. But this needs to be a family of super heroes ready to care for him, flaws and all! We know how loving Cooper is. Are you ready to step up and be this sweet guy's super hero family?

SPIN Pyrs are all in foster homes in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. Potential adopters are asked to make travel arrangements if they live elsewhere. All SPIN dogs are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and on heartworm prevention. Please go to our website www.SpinRescue.org and fill out an application for this great Great Pyrenees! 2/2/21 4:51 PM

Hi there! 
My name is Sadie. I’m a Mama of 11 (maybe more, but this was the last litter of mine), and I want nothing else but to have a family of my own where I can crash forever.  I have a lot of love to give and was a very attentive and patient mom to my pups. I’m still young and playful, though, and can’t wait to live a fun filled life. I like to go on leisurely walks and do well on a leash. No pulling. I have lived with other dogs of various sizes in my foster home and get along well with them. But I would also enjoy being an only dog with my human doting on me.   While I enjoy walks, I also enjoy just to veg out and not doing much of anything. Come meet me! 

**We do require you to own your home to adopt this dog due to her size and breed resemblance (this will be checked before application is approved).

**If interested in adopting, please submit the adoption application on our website pp2crescue.com. We will be accepting applications, and will mark as pending adoption when no longer available.  Please do not submit an inquiry unless you have a specific question about the dog. We do not have the time or manpower to answer multiple emails asking if the dog is still available, your best chance at adopting is submitting the application. **

animal.description:
Lily's smile is contagious! She approx 4-5 yo and is a big sweetheart and goofball who needs some help building her confidence (and not that false bravado she puts on when she’s scared). Although we only know part of this sweet girl’s story, it’s enough to know she’s been through a lot. Lily was found abandoned after her last family moved away and when she arrived at the shelter, she had patches of missing hair, scrapes, a nail in her paw, sores on her paw, and a fist-sized ulcerated mass. She was put on a shortened rescue timeline for her medical issues. Her euthanasia date came and went as the shelter dragged it out as long as possible to try to get her rescued. South County Tail Waggers generously stepped in to save her, but her journey was only starting.

Lily is a lazy, sweet girl who loves to give kisses, loves belly rubs, and is perfectly happy to just sleep all day. She also LOVES her daily walks and looks forward to them. She is a smart girl who catches on to routines and expectations quickly. She is very responsive to verbal correction and does a good job of respecting boundaries once they're established. She needs a home with someone who can see through her bluffs, but who will also not let her run the household (because she will, if you let her haha). She is working on her socialization and it takes a while for her to warm up to men in particular (though it took a few days, she adores her foster dad!). 

She is interested in other dogs and even play bows and cries if she sees them playing, but is shy once they approach and will let it be known if she's not comfortable. While she can be a couch potato, she also loves going on long walks and hikes, etc.

Lily believes the best defense is a good offense and can act out aggressively when afraid (though she prefers to just avoid the scary thing). She is learning how to relax and not be so guarded. When we come home, she will smile as she excitedly brings you whatever is nearby as a present to let you know how much she missed you (sometimes that's her favorite toy...sometimes it's your favorite shoe, but she is very gentle with both).

She is a silly, goofy girl who will steal your heart. We love her and think you will too!

*** Since this bio has been written, Lily has gone through an intensive 4 week board and train program (worth over $2K) and she did an AMAZING job while she was there! Once she graduated she came out almost like a different dog. She is an absolute love, and we honestly have zero idea on why she hasn't been adopted yet!!?? Her adoption will also come with 5 in-home private training lessons with her trainer Franck. Whomever is lucky enough to get to adopt Lily will be the better ones for it for SURE.

We think Lily will be able to be around children that are older and more dog savvy. She would not be OK with a young child poking or prodding her, etc. 

*** Lily has had several meet and greets and everyone has passed on her thus far because she wasn't immediately and overly affectionate, however she has done her absolute best and has even rolled on her back to allow some belly rubs. After each time someone passes on her we just shake our heads in disappointment because these people have no idea the gem they are passing on! She just needs a little time, and we clearly haven't found the person/family worthy of her yet. But we know there are out there!!! 

Could it be you??

The latest video we posted of Lily is her TRUE self -- this is how she acts when she trusts the humans around her. Here she is being picked up by her foster Dad after being at daycare . . . 


Please complete an adoption application on our website at www.sctailwaggers.org/adopt. Please also take this opportunity to read more about SCTW and about our adoption process, etc.

animal.description:
Meet Charlie Woo, a 3-yr old Labradoodle. Charlie is a gorgeous boy who is looking for his forever family.

Charlie is adorable and affectionate, is crate trained and obedient, and walks beautifully on leash. However, he does have special behavioral needs and needs an experienced dog parent!

Charlie has triggers that will lead him to snap or bite; his foster mom is still working with him to discover these triggers, but so far, leaning over him or getting too close into his space can trigger him.

For these reasons, only homes with the following will be considered for Charlie:

-No small children (living permanently or who visit regularly);

-No small pets (dogs or cats)

-Must have a fenced yard for safe play and training

Due to his triggers, Charlie should not be taken to dog parks.

To find his ideal home, multiple meet and greets will be held to ensure a great match for all involved; therefore, no out of state applications can be considered.

Somewhere in his past life, people failed this precious boy. He's just waiting for the right people to find him who can work with him and show him how good people can be!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
Shep arrived at Horse Creek Wildlife Sanctuary on March 19, 2020.  

He is extremely friendly and acts just like a puppy!  He prefers human companionship and tries desperately to please.  Shep plays well with other dogs and enjoys spending time running and romping in our exercise areas.

He is still growing, and we believe he could be a Lab mix. 

Shep will make a great addition to a loving and caring family. Are you that special someone who can give him the home he dreams of?

All of our dogs are spayed or neutered and are current on all vaccinations. They are on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. All of their medical needs are taken care of before they are available for adoption. Our adoption fee is only $100.00. Please complete an application, if you have found a dog you are interested in adopting. You can find our application at www.horsecreekwildlife.org/applic.html. Once completed, you can forward it to adoptions@horsecreekwildlife.org or fax it to 731-926-3000. Kim Austin, our adoption facilitator, will be in contact with you as soon as she has an opportunity to review your application. Understand that she has other duties and she will not ignore any interest shown in adopting one of our dogs. An application will need to be approved before a scheduled time to visit our dogs will be set up.  It may take up to 48 hours before she returns your call or responds to your email, due to work schedules, holidays and adoption events. We do the very best we can for the dogs we have rescued and do not take the adoption process lightly. Please be patient and understand that we will place our rescued dogs in the very best homes possible and reserve the right to refuse applications.

animal.description:
Hi there! My name is Quinta, but i go by Quinnie. I am eight and a 45 lb female lab retriever. I enjoy walks, runs, playing fetch but then i also love my cuddling, chillin, and long naps time. Once you feed me, ill need a belly rub and ill go roll around in the green lawn. I love my humans. All I want is a home and a family to keep me safe. Young children are not my favorite because they make sudden screams and movements. I prefer a home with kids that have at least 13 years of life experience. Im incredibly sweet and loyal and love an active well-balanced-with-snuggles lifestyle. I am told i have the the best smile ever - seems to get me lots of hugs and treats. I know to go potty outside, i walk nicely on a leash, and now sit, shake, and high five on command. My dog trainer said wow, she is very trainable so i cant wait to keep learning what i need to do. My foster family has 2 small dogs - ive decided they are fine now, but in the beginning i was like who are these dudes? With a slow intro, now we all hang out and we play fetch, chase, and take walks and naps together.

Now heres a word from my fosters 13 year old daughter that i follow around obsessively and love with all my heart, Quinta is really sweet and all cuddles and just hangs out with me. She sleeps on my bed at nights, but she is fine sleeping in a crate too but i like her cuddles. She just wants to be with me wherever i go. She relaxes on the couch with me to watch a movie, on the bed, next to my desk, takes naps with me and if i go on a walk, she is the happiest. We even go on runs together. Her smiles makes my worries melt away and she will fill the hearts of her new furrever home family.

*Homeownership required!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration

animal.description: Do you like smart dogs who love to play games with their brains in the house? Vin Diesel is a super smart boy who needs to exercise his brain just as much if not more than his body. He loves to do scent work, practice his commands, and play tug-o-war. All these get his brain working! Vin D. will happily settle near your feet after some much-deserved playtime. Due to tendon issues with his front feet, Vin Diesel has an unusual strut and prefers short walks with a muzzle that keeps him from reacting to other dogs. Then he gets to spend more time cuddling with his people. Do you like to sleep? So does Vin! The boy loves to sleep with his belly up right next to his human. When it's time to rise and shine, he is happy to have you wake him with sweet whispers. He is house-trained, and when you're not home, he happily goes in his crate and sleeps like a baby with blankets and a soft bed, waiting patiently for his people to come back home. This handsome boy is looking for a patient, adult-only family that will play with him in a yard, take him on short walks, and let him snooze on his doggie bed. He can get overly excited about new human friends and dog friends and is on medication to help calm him. So, a low-traffic neighborhood and home with a quiet yard and where he's the only fur kid is ideal. He could go home with a well-matched dog companion after slow introductions. In return, Diesel will be the best little boy he can be and repay you in endless kisses! Vin Diesel is upping his skills game to impress his new parents. He is perfecting his 'sit,' 'down,' and 'place' through APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP). To learn more about his training, check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP is based: https://vimeo.com/89434193. Come meet Vin Diesel, he'd love to show you his belly!
