animal.description: Mandy was surrendered by her owner, mostly due to incompatibility with another dog living in the home. She will require quite a bit of supervision, so it may be best for her to be the only dog in any event. Mandy appears to be a combination of Doberman, black Lab, and Greyhound, as she's built like a Greyhound but with the coloring of a Lab, and she had a sibling that looked mostly Dobie. She's about 3 years old and is housebroken, is affectionate and loves to play. She can be stubborn about following commands, and she was destructive when she was younger, needing a lot of stimulation and entertainment. Unfortunately, Mandy can also jump an 8-foot fence, so she would need to be kenneled in a very secure kennel when it is necessary to leave her home alone. A person or couple who work from home would probably be the most ideal home for Mandy, but again, with close supervision; she has been known to "counter surf" and could potentially even decide to depart over a fence even with people present at home.  Her ex-owner said she requires EVERY family member to be home.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Sawyer Brown was wandering the streets in a small town in South Texas. Some folks tossed their leftovers out to feed him, and others mostly ignored him. Then one day, one person threatened to shoot him, so a local rescuer was called to save the day. She picked him up and took him to the vet to be scanned for a microchip. He didn't have one/ During his stray hold, she posted photos, and a variety of people said they remembered seeing him hang around town, but no one claimed him. So once his stray hold was up, Sawyer Brown headed north to Windsong Ranch.

Sawyer shows great guardian instincts, so we have been testing him with our livestock. He hasn't been consistently reliable with our goats, so we think he should go to a home where the only thing he is asked to guard is his home and human family. We also think he would do best in a home where he is the only dog, as he can be very picky about which dogs he gets along with. He hasn't gotten along with any of the male dogs we have introduced him to, and he seems to just tolerate female dogs. If you have a female dog whose personality is not alpha, we would be glad to do a meet & greet to see whether she and Sawyer might be friends.

If Sawyer sounds like exactly the right guardian for you and your home, please complete the application on our website.

animal.description:
Sweet, Empathetic Brody Needs a Home to Call His Own!

Besides being super adorable and cuddly (and having the softest and warmest floppy ears), Brody is also uber sweet and sensitive.

This young boy's story has not always been happy. He was found as a stray, abandoned by his adoptive family 90 miles from home. Thankfully he has retained his optimism, and continues to hope and trust that one day he will find his very own humans again to love him, be kind to him and make him the center of their world.

Brody - or Bro Bro as he prefers to be endearingly addressed - is THE best hiking companion. He is energetic and thoroughly enjoys daily walks around the neighborhood. But he especially LOVES hiking adventures in the woods. Nothing makes him happier than car rides.

Bro Bro is also a big homebody and enjoys chillin' in front of a good Netflix too. He loves piano music - his favorite spots in his foster family's home are under the baby grand when it's being played and on the couch snuggling on a quiet rainy day.

We believe that Bro Bro's not-so-happy first part of his life has given him the special gift of empathy. He is ultra sensitive and attuned to the emotions of his humans.

When he senses that people are sad, he has been known to promptly walk over and place his warm comforting head firmly on their lap as his way of saying, "Please feel better. Bro Bro is here for you forever and is your friend. I will snuggle with you now if you like."

He has a ridiculously adorable spazzy side too. And he most often exhibits that when his humans come home. That's when he does The Dance - a combination of extreme butt wiggles and whirling dervish spinning while holding his favorite toy in his mouth.

Bro Bro will thrive in a home where he can shine as the only pet, and will be happiest with calm, kind and gentle adults who are experienced adopters and can continue to train him using the gentlest ways - we strongly recommend Jan Fennell's Amichien Bonding method, rather than Cesar Milan's physical domination approach.

When Bro Bro knows in his heart that he is forever loved and is safe and will never be scolded, he will blossom and make you so proud by being your best and most loyal furry forever friend! 

...If you live with an hour of Washington, D.C. and have a fenced yard, please apply to adopt this sweet soul! His adoption fee is $125, he is neutered, is current on rabies, dhpp, bordatella and has been on monthly preventatives for fleas/ticks and heartworms. He's been getting the best nutrition possible too I might add. Best with no children in the home, adults ideal. This 7 year old boy needs you and you will be rewarded with his love in return! Please share this post also if you would!

Can you be his family?! Committed fosters or foster to adopt, please contact us also! Transport is available in VA or D.C area to an approved home.
animal.name: Brody

animal.description:
Oh sweet Raven, while we cannot erase your past we can promise you that we will give you the future you have always deserved. Raven, a 9 month old Dane, was found along the interstate and taken to a local shelter where she served her stray time. It was clear to the shelter workers that Raven has never spent any time indoors nor had she been socialized with much of anything to include humans. She was just trembling and would cower in her kennel, couldn't walk with a leash on and would just pancake on the floor and not move. They knew that this sweet girl needed one on one time with a foster to help her learn about the world around her. She needed to learn to trust humans, to learn about other dogs and animals and how to live inside a home so they reached out to BDHP to help her and we are honored to be able to give Raven all that she needs to include a wonderful forever home that will love and care for her always. She may take a little time to blossom but we know that her foster family will give her all the tools to help her grow and learn and we cannot wait to see the beautiful butterfly she will turn into; welcome to the family Raven.

Giant Breed Experienced Homes Only.

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

animal.description:
LILY IS NOT AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION.

LILY IS A SPECIAL NEEDS PUP WHO NEEDS SPONSORSHIP.

Hi. My name is Lily. I'm an 11-year old tiny Maltese mix senior girl. I weigh less than six pounds. But my big personality more than makes up for my small size. I've been living with my foster family for more than two years. They really love me and I love them back. My mom says I'm like a little wind-up toy because I run in little circles right after my walks and then hop into my bed for a nice long nap. I love to follow my family around, but I cuddle with them only when I want to. I'm independent that way. I sleep soundly in my crate all night long. My mom says it's safer for a little girl like me to be in a crate at night, and that's fine by me. I love my crate. My family cares about me so much that they're spending lots of time treating all my medical conditions. They put medicine in my eyes twice a day and they feed me the right foods so I don't get an allergic reaction, I have a tendency to get yeast infections. To avoid that, my mom gives me a bath with antiseptic shampoo twice a week. She uses Q-tips with Witch Hazel to clean my ears and the spaces between my toes. It's uncomfortable but I let her do it. I know it's for my own good. My family works so hard to make sure I'm as healthy and comfortable as I can possibly be. My eyesight is limited, but I still look up at my family and wag my tail happily when they're around. It makes me so happy to be near them. Because I can't hear anything anymore, my mom wakes me up by gently shaking my crate so she doesn't scare me. My mom is very considerate of my special needs.

As you can imagine, my medical care costs a lot of money. Would you consider sponsoring me so my foster family can keep taking care of me? Anything you can afford would be so appreciated. If you want, my mom can send you pictures of me so you see how I'm doing and how your donations are helping me.

If you would like to sponsor me, please copy and paste this link: https://bichonrescueoc.org/sponsorship

SWEET SOUTHERN BELLE WAITING FOR A HOME. Tia is a healthy, sensitive beagle in her prime. She has been in foster care a long time, healing physically and emotionally from a troubled past. When she first came to TDR, she was so skittish she didn't want to be touched by humans, but she has warmed up considerably. Tia is about five years old, house trained and gets along well with other dogs. Tia would be an excellent companion for an individual, a pair of empty nesters or retirees.
A quiet home with a fenced-in yard to help Tia feel secure is ideal. She has allergies and needs to have shots a few times each year to prevent her skin from breaking out. She's also on a special diet. She is spayed, up to date on all of her vaccinations, microchipped and heart worm negative. More than anything, Tia needs patient and loving people who will gently help her come out of her shell and continue healing. She is sponsored by a TDR Angel, so her new owners don't have to pay an adoption fee. Available at Tired Dog Rescue in Gulfport, MS. animal.description:
Armando was brought in to Houston high kill shelter to put him down .

He showed aggression to the staff and his time was up . As rescuers we know it is very rare that a dog is really aggressive so I took my chance and took him out of there ... and I’m very happy I did .

Yes and our vet he was not a happy trooper either but the poor thing had a horrible ear infection. Yes, you read that right . He would have been killed over an ear infection that the owner did not want to treat . Don’t you love people ?

Armando arrived after being fully medical treated but I thought he was still too skinny so he stayed a while at our vet in Huntington . He looks good now. A few pounds extra I would not mind but we are always careful with German Shepherds and weight on their hips .

A wagging tail , big eyes and happy smile when I opened his kennel for the first time to walk him in the woods . This Godzilla of a dog is nothing more then a sweet shepherd who loves to hike . There was totally not an issue with him . Still he is a German shepherd and we only adopt him out to shepherd experienced owners .

His previous owner clearly did not care about him so he receives all the love he can get from us .

Armando is 5 years old . Does not like cats or dogs and has to be pet only .

We would love to see him with a wonderful person who sees the same great boy in him as I see .

Somebody who will love him forever and gives him everything he needs .

Armando is located in Middle Island .

To become an approved adopter you have to fill in the adoption application to find on our website www.a-teameliterescuedogs.com or email us and we send you one

animal.description:
* SPECIAL NEEDS - PROTECTIVE, STRANGER DANGER *
Hey there I'm Mickey! I'm an 8 year old boy. Some of my best friends could tell you just how loyal and loveable I truly am. I'm so loyal that when around my favorite people, I want to protect them. I would love someone who will keep me as active as my age would allow, as I do love to go for walks and even love to swim! Stranger danger is a term that my friends might use to describe me but it's really because when I love you, I want to protect you and my space from other people! I would want to protect you even from your friends, so keep in mind I would likely need my own room of a big comfy crate to hang out in if you have company over. I could potentially live with another submissive dog, but we would have to meet and form a friendship first. I would be best in a home with no kids. My favorite activities include exploring new places (where they're aren't many people), swimming in safe places (even a kiddie pool) and going on car rides! I also love to get pet and receive love from my best friends. I would want to meet you a few times before I would be comfortable with you, but if you give me treats, throw my toys for me, and come on a few walks, I'm sure we would become great friends. I really hope you'll come meet me, and don't mind that I require a little patience. Hope to meet you soon! Love, Mickey
*Mickey has extreme protective tendencies and would need to be in a home where no one comes in and out of the home without a careful introduction. It will take several visits to the shelter for Mickey to feel comfortable with you.

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org

Hi! I am Dexter! Sometimes I am called Dex, sometimes I only answer to Mr. Handsome. I am a cuddly, fun guy who has recovered from paralysis. I had a back injury, likely due to genetics, and I had the surgery to fix it. Due to my back, I should not do stairs. After I rehabbed, I can walk again although I am wobbly and have some bathroom accidents when I don't make it to the doggie door in time. I love to rip apart my stuffed toys and hang with the other foster dogs. I am quiet and easy going. My favorite place to hang out is in the kitchen because that is where the snacks live. Meeting new people is no problem for me because I am friendly and charming. Having someone home with me all the time would be a dream come true, but I can certainly nap while you go to work if that means more snacks and toys, but I will need attention and love when you come home. I enjoy the company of other dogs and pretty much ignore the cat.

I have a secret superpower! Go look at my video and you can see that I know how to arrange my own covers and tuck myself in to bed. It took my foster mom a while but she finally got it on video. I know, pretty cool if I say so myself.

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

animal.description:
Bentley is a friendly Pit Bull Terrier mix, born May, 2017. He is so social! Loves to be around people. Loves to play with toys with people.He is potty trained- never had an accident coming to his new foster home. He loves walks but needs to be on a leash. He is a little rambunctious because he likes to chase birds, rabbits,etc. but is already learning new commands like leave it. He learns quickly and never wants to disappoint his family. Bentley is not a fan of being alone and after being kenneled( he does well) he will stay by your side for awhile.Bentley is good around all people but needs to be in a one dog family, a fenced yard and a house full of tough toys.

The suggested adoption donation for Bentley is $300. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

ALEKI was trying to survive on the streets of Texas when animal control picked him . His paperwork was made . STRAY in fat letters and the clock started to tick for him

In a high kill shelter with a daily intake of more then hundred dogs there was no chance to stay alive . One dead body after the other is what the reality is .

Only rescue was his only chance so we took him safe under our wings . Skin in over bones, ready eyes . He was a mess so we rushed him to our vet and today ... well today he s a very handsome fellow .

He has that special tip on his ear and when he is making a head tilt with it he is just plain adorable .

He loved walking in the woods and his tail was going up and down .

ALEKI is around 3 years old . He is good with other dogs but not with cats 

He is a very good boy and a happy fellow . Not to difficult on the leash but likes to smell everything.

ALEKI is located in Middle island.

We would love to see him coming him to a great family who will just love him and gives him the quality time he needs .

If you would like to give him his forever home then please apply today by filling in the  adoption  link to find on our website or email us and we send you one .

animal.description:
Cody is a 5 - 6 year old Boxer mix who is looking for a loving, active and structured forever home! He is sweet but had a rough beginning so will need a rescue experienced home that will help him build trust, learn basic obedience and gain confidence. 

He will bond to his people and loves attention and affection. He loves treats and is glad to work for them! He has not had a lot of training so will need support with continued basic obedience. 

He is looking for a home that is adult only or with kids over the age of 16. He will thrive in a home where he can be active, he loves to run around, go for walks, and would make an excellent outdoor activity partner.

Cody can do well with other dogs but it is always best to do proper introductions to make sure it is a good match and that all parties 'mesh'. Cody would do best in a home with a large fenced yard where he can run, roam and play. 

Cody is UTD on shots, has had a dental, is microchipped and neutered. His adoption fee is $400.

animal.description:
Medical costs to date: $650.98

Mac is not available for out of area adoption.

Mac is yet another Scottie in need of our help. At just 3 years of age, he lost his home due to the pandemic and to top that off, he has severe skin issues that are needing to be evaluated at our vet.

9-2-20: While we have been aggressively treating Mac's skin allergies, it is apparent that he will need ongoing care, such as monthly Cytopoint injections and weekly medicated baths. We hope to find Mac a Scottie experienced home in the DFW area.

5-29-20 Mac was taken back to the vet today for an infections in both ears. After testing and cleaning, treatment was begun with a long-term (30-day) medication.

5-20-20 Mac has received all of his vaccinations, blood tests and an injection to help calm his irritated skin. He will be on oral medications for 2-3 weeks, then re-evaluated to determine when he will be available for adoption.

5-18-20 Mac will be seen by our vet today, to evaluate his skin problems, as well as a full physical exam, blood tests and vaccinations that are overdue.

Please help Mac by donating to his care. We have taken in several Scotties in need over the past few months, all of which needed extensive medical care. PayPal to Donate@scottiekingdom.com or you may send a check to Scottie Kingdom Rescue, Inc - PO Box 551265 - Dallas, TX 75355. All donations are acknowledged.

All dogs adopted by Scottie Kingdom Rescue, Inc. have had a full medical exam by one of our licensed Veterinarians, which includes testing (and treatment, if necessary) for Heartworm disease, Lyme disease, Ehrlichia and Anaplasmosis, all necessary vaccinations, spay/neuter surgery, dental cleaning as necessary, microchipping, registration of the microchip, and any other medical needs each particular dog may need. Copies of all available medical records are transferred to you when the adoption is finalized.

We prefer to adopt to families with past Scottie, Westie, Terrier experience, but realize this isn't always possible. We do NOT ship our pets. If you have that special place in your heart, and in your home, for a Scottie (or any of our other available rescue dogs), please visit us in Dallas for an in person meet & greet session with our available dogs. If you have existing dogs, they should travel to Dallas with you, so we can be assured that they will be compatible with the new addition to your family.

Please contact us at
Rescue@scottiekingdom.com
to receive an Adoption Application or for more information on our Adoption process. Also, please take the time to visit our website
www.scottiekingdom.com
for additional information.

We sometimes receive several applications on the same dog. Our goal is to place the dog in the best home possible, based on his/her needs, personality and past history. Please note: Adoptions are not done on a first come, first served basis. Submitting an application does not guarantee the adoption of any dog. We are looking for the best available home for each of our rescue dogs.

Thank you for your understanding, and for considering adoption!

We are
not
supported by your tax dollars or public grants, rather, we rely on donations to help us continue our rescue work for animals that are in need.

Donations may be made via PayPal to email address:

Donate@scottiekingdom.com

or via USPS, to PO Box 551265 ~ Dallas, TX

75355

animal.description:
Meg came into rescue with her littermate Amy. These two cuties are very sweet and love attention.  They were found as strays and not reclaimed by the owner.  We estimate they were born in July of 2018.    They both enjoy belly rubs and Meg likes to squint her eyes up at you when she's happy. The girls are very bonded and a home together would be "pyrfect" for them.  We hate to split up families. They are smaller pyrs, about 60 lbs. and are very gentle and friendly. 
 They are fine with male dogs,selective with other female dogs, and are unproven with cats.  We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heart worm preventative year round for your dogs. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 5 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $300

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS FOR NEWT:

KIDS 12 AND OVER ONLY.
FULLY FENCED YARD.
DAILY MEDS FOR ALLERGIES.
PATIENCE SINCE HE IS SHY WITH STRANGERS.


Newt is formally Skye, a chihuahua/terrier mix, about 12 pounds. He was born to Smidget Sonya at the rescue in 2017 and adopted out as a 4 month old puppy. Now three years old, he was surrendered after becoming too protective of their newborn. He is SMART and food motivated, which means he will be easy to train and would probably love some type of agility work or activity that gets him busy. He is definitely out of sorts and nervous, wondering when they are going to come back and pick him up. We are learning more about him each day. Right now, we know that he LOVES to play with other dogs and also loves his chin rubbed. He appears devoted to his humans and wants to be near you when he's comfortable. He will need someone who is willing to work with him, as he appears to be under-socialized with strangers. He wants to protect you and his turf and will demonstrate reactivity on leash and in the yard to those not in his family. We recommend no kids under 10. He has some allergies that are currently being treated with Apoquel. We were told he is afraid of thunderstorms. Overall he is a fun, energetic and loyal fellow! 

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.   Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Nip has spent his life guarding goats, and he takes his job seriously. He is friendly with people, but unfortunately, he is reactive to a leash or collar, which makes it a real challenge to take him to the vet. Nip's original owner bought him as a puppy, brought him home, and put him with goats. He loved his dog, but apparently never saw the need to put a collar or leash on him, and never took him to the vet. We are working to de-sensitize Nip, to show him that we can put a light slip lead around his neck and it won't harm him. We are currently using a lightweight plastic goat chain, which you can see in some of his photos. It breaks easily, so we replace it regularly, but he still gets nervous when we slip it over his head. For this reason, we think it would be best if Nip could be adopted by someone who has a vet who makes farm/ranch calls, to minimize the stress of trying to get him the care he needs.

animal.description:
Allow us to introduce you to this beautiful ray of sunshine, Skylar! 

Sky arrived with us in February when she pregnant. She gave birth at the shelter and struggled. Only 3 of her pups survived and you could see the sadness within her. 

This beautiful red head has learned what true love is and how great life can be when she let's people love her. I will warn you though, she is about 50lbs and definately thinks she is a lap dog. :)
Skylar is good on leash and enjoys walking, sniffing and being by your side. 

Skylar had a very ruff start in life. In her previous life, she was shown early on to keep mom safe, which to this day makes her uneasy with men. She came from a life of yelling and fighting.

Sky would excel in a quiet home, sharing her life with a mom. She loves to hike, go for rides and she loves to make ya laugh! 

Stop by, meet Sky! Spend some quality time with her over a period of time. The slow pace approach is what will win her over!

Don't let the gray fool you! Checkers is only 4 1/2 and full of energy, spunk and lots of love to give. Checkers is a 70-80 pound Great Dane/Irish Wolfhound (hence the gray) mix and is ready to find his forever home!

Checkers is a very happy go lucky kind guy, and is ready for whatever adventure you want to go on. He loves walks, playing and also getting love, pets and attention. He will benefit from a family that can work on some basic training with him but is very teachable and treat motivated. 

Checkers is picky with other dogs and can be reactive when on a leash. He will require a family that knows how to handle his strength and will invest in professional training with him. He may do okay with a laid back female dog in the home after some training, but we think he would do best as an only dog at this time. He is not a dog park dog. 

Checkers will need a fully fenced yard with room for him to play. no apartments as he is very large, strong and has lots of energy. We are looking for a family that is experienced with either Irish Wolfhounds or Great Danes

We think Checkers would be fine with kids but we recommend older kids since he could easily knock over small children. No toddlers or cats for him!

Checkers is UTD on shots, microchipped and neutered. His adoption fee is $400.

animal.description:
Meet the happy jumping Jack! Jack is a 1.5 year old Pitbull/Hound mix. Jack and his housemate Rose were surrendered by their previous owner to a local veterinary hospital and came to RR in disturbing shape. Jack weighed 20# upon intake and Rose weighed 18#; both were severely malnourished and had pressure sores from staying crated for extended periods of time. They have been in RR care for 6 weeks as of 5/13/20; and now Jack weighs 38# while Rose weighs 37#. Both of them have a long journey ahead of them, but are already thriving with their regular diet and some attention. While we thought Jack and Rose were a bonded pair and needed to stay together; Jack has become very aggressive with Rose over food, toys, treats, and attention. Now that both are receiving regular love and affection; Jack gets easily jealous of Rose.  He will need to be the only animal in the home (no other dogs or cats) as he has a high prey drive and toy drive. Jack is learning how to play, though he often shreds stuffed toys. He does best with heavy duty toys (like Kong balls and tug toys) that can stand up to his vigorous playtime! Jack is also learning how to leash walk (he pulls pretty intensely), and is learning some basic commands. He has mastered sit, and will often sit for a treat without being told to. Jack is also learning how to take treats more gently, he is very enthusiastic about food/treats and can be a little grabby when fed. Jack has some major crate and separation anxiety; he is working through this but will take a lot of patience and time to recover from the neglect he and Rose endured. Jack has made so much improvement over the past 6 weeks and would excel in a loving home with someone that would be willing to help him overcome his anxiety issues and show him what a real loving home has to offer! No animal should be treated the way Jack and Rose were cared for.

7/8/20 UPDATE: Jack now weighs 52 lbs and is at an appropriate weight! He is starting Fluoxetine today, a medication to help with his anxiety. Hopefully he will do well on the medication and become a less anxious boy.

8/24/20 UPDATE: We decided to hold off on Jack's anti-anxiety medication due to Rose's adoption earlier this month and he is much more calm without interacting with Rose. He is starting to pay attention to us more and patiently waits for meal times or treats. We hope that by removing the anxious element (Rose being adopted) that he will continue to relax and we can move forward with some training!

11/15/20 UPDATE: We had another photo shoot today (since Jack's most recent pictures were taken in May when he was only weighing about 38 lbs). We haven't done a weigh in for a bit and estimate Jack is now about 65 lbs. Jack has started a walking regimen to help ensure he doesn't get too heavy, and he loves his walks! Jack walks best with a pinch collar as he is a big boy and can pull pretty hard when he sees something he wants to investigate! He loves going for walks with AJ (the resident 3 year old) and is learning not to get so excitable around him. Jack is continuing to thrive and is still searching for his forever home!

animal.description:
This is Martin, a one year old, 54 pound blue pit bull terrier.  Martin is a nerd. This dog is super happy, very bouncy and he needs a home that wants a dog who wants to go for a run. He has energy to burn and he needs a home that can do that, whether it's a 2 mile run or chucking a ball for him to chase for 20 minutes. Without adequate energy burned, Martin gets excited and then he gets mouthy and people do not enjoy being treated like a live squeaky toy. Martin can get along with other dogs, but his energy level is high and a lot of dogs will not appreciate that. Given the variables in the world, I think it is best that he be in an only dog home but know that with work and careful introductions with a dog with boundless energy and no snark, Martin is fine. I would not put this dog in a home with cats under any circumstances. Small woodland creatures, either, so if you run a sanctuary for harmless fluffy bunnies, this is not your dog.

Martin is incredibly sweet and very affectionate. He adores everyone and does not know a stranger. He is very well mannered in the home and he knows commands. He waits patiently to be fed and gives you mournful looks while you are filling his bowl. He loves his toys and he loves to snuggle on the couch. I think a home with kids over 12 (bounce factor weighs in on the age of kids he is appropriate for) and a securely fenced wooden fence are best.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ and then email kim.tompkins@bigfluffydogs.com. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

IF YOU HAVE ROOM IN YOUR HOME AND HEART TO FOSTER HER AND HER SISTER GINNY, PLEASE CONTACT US.  SHE HAS NOT BEEN AROUND CATS BUT IS CURRENTLY IN A HOME WITH SEVERAL OTHER DOGS OTHER THAN HER SISTER GINNY.  SHE DOES, HOWEVER, LOVE TO CHASE SQUIRRELS.  SHE HAS NEVER CAUGHT ONE BUT WE FEEL THAT SHE WOULD BE A THREAT TO ANY SMALL ANIMAL.  SO A CAT FREE HOME IS A MUST!!!!

Winny is currently being fostered in north carolina. She will hop on her freedom flight north once we have a comitted and approved home to place her.

An application and home visit (outdoor only / virtual indoor) are required for placement of any of our precious rescues. Winny's adoption fee is $400.

There is no fee to foster. You simply care for and love Winny and sister Ginny while they wait for their family to find them. It is not expected to be long for these beautiful  girls.

animal.description: This handsome 2 year old German Shepherd is SPORT!  Sport belonged to an Amish gentleman as a “shop” dog however he retired and sold the shop. He spent most of his life in a 10x10 kennel, overstimulated, stressed and frustrated that he couldn’t interact with things on the other side of the fence. He remains friendly with most people that he meets out and about however he has been protective and given warning bites when he feels he needs to protect his family inside his home/yard. All of these bites have occurred during our initial two week shelter shut down and, to Sport's benefit, the shut down was not carried out properly in any of the circumstances. However we now know this is a problem and need his new family to be completely serious with following our instructions on how to best integrate Sport. He is currently in a foster home and doing well. Sport is extremely reactive to other dogs during his walks on leash. He needs to work on de-escalating and we recommend working with a trainer. We do require that his new home have a fenced yard and preferably a privacy fence and not in a development setting. His ideal home would be in a country setting without a lot of visitors and a family that can work on the bad habits that he picked up while guarding the shop. His new family must have similar dog experience. Not just “I grew up with German Shepherds” but actual experience in dealing with a reactive dog. A fenced yard is a must but we do want him to have exercise outside of a fenced yard - hikes in a park, obedience class, anything to exercise his brain as German shepherds need a job to make them feel fulfilled. The old adage “a tired puppy is a good puppy“ definitely applies to Sport! He does ride well in a car!  Sport does need an adult only home with no other pets at this time.  Sport has been neutered, vaccinated, tested negative for heartworms and microchipped. Adoption $250. Please fill out an application at www.companimals.org and tell us what you can offer Sport!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Hi, everyone! My name is Thor. What's yours? The folks here at Rescue Ridge in Monmouth County NJ say that I am an incredibly handsome, 8 yrs.old Bulldog just waiting for the right person or family to come along. I have been waiting for quite a while now for the right home. The volunteers at Rescue Ridge understand me. You see, I have this thing called arthritis and sometimes I just don't f
eel like moving much or I get grumpy sometimes. They have me on some medicine and that really helps me to get around much better. In fact, I feel even better when I go on easy-going walks and I am really good on a leash. I am housebroken, too. I LOVE car rides so let me be your co-pilot. My friends at Rescue Ridge even got me some professional training and I have done really well...graduating with high honors or something like that:) I am best in an adult home and am dog selective. I prefer mellow dogs or ones who are polite to an older guy like me. I would love an experienced owner who understands that I have had to endure a lot in my lifetime and will be your absolute most loyal and loving, affectionate companion once I know you. You see, I really am a good guy so please apply to adopt me at Rescueridge.com No inquiries, please, without an application. Kennel life is hard for an older guy like me. Won't you please adopt me soon? Here I am in my video debut. Pull up a chair and take a look

https://youtu.be/TEYXF5LOEA0

animal.description:
If you're looking for a mellow cuddle-bug, then Pepito is your man! He is a 13 year old Chihuahua with lots of love to give. He enjoys long walks in the neighborhood, naps right next to his human, assisting in the kitchen, and bath time.
Although Pepito is not very playful, he is good with children and other dogs.
Pepito was surrendered to a vets office when his owner slipped into a coma.
Overall, Pepito would be a lovely addition to a loving family.
Pepito does best to go out about every 4 hours. Perfect dog for a house with easy access to a small back yard or play area. Loves to play in the morning and at meal times, quiet the rest of the time. Will occasionally realize he has a tail and growl and chase it.'

Pepito was surrendered to a local vet when his owner slipped into a coma and could no longer care for him.

We only do adoptions on Saturday and not all animals are able to attend so if you would like to see a specific animal please let us know so that we can make arrangements for it to be present at the event. Event locations do vary so please check the homepage to find out where we will be this week. Please do not ask us to reduce adoption fees since all fees help us to cover medical expenses for all of our animals, some of which can be very expensive. PLEASE NOTE: Petey will ONLY be adopted into a home in the Sequim area as it will take several home visits before he will be comfortable moving into a new home. 

Petey is an adorable young pup born on 3/5/20.  He was found running wild in a rural area and had obviously never had any human contact. He is still very shy and anxious, but with lots of loving interaction with both humans and confident dogs, he is making great progress!

Petey will need a home with a young, playful dog to help him learn the ropes and build his confidence. He will do best with an owner who has experience with timid pups and has the patience and time to spend with him. We don't know how he would react to cats or other pets in the home. He does need a home with no children under the age of 12 please.

Most of our dogs require a fully fenced yard, this does depend on the individual dogs needs and safety requirements.  

Our dogs are fed a nutrient rich dog food named NutriSource.  Our experience is a high quality dog food keeps vet bills down and well-being high.

If you have any questions please email: claudiaatwag@gmail.com

Visit our website to fill out an Adoption Application  http://www.wagsequimwa.com

Adoption donation fee $350  (Please understand this adoption donation goes towards helping all the dogs we rescue)

animal.description:
Meet Prince! 

*** Prince's Adoption fee has been sponsored by Sharon and Bill Mack in memory of their beloved Gideon.***

Could this be your Prince Charming? Ever wonder what it's like to have someone look deep into your soul with eyes overflowing with love? Adopt Prince and you'll never feel lonely again! Prince is a medium sized, 67 pounds (but should be closer to 50) 7 year old lab/pittie mix that will conquer your heart! He has the shiniest black coat, beautiful dark amber eyes, and a tail that never stops wagging! Prince's favorite things are cookies, pets, balls, gentle kisses, and chew toys in that order and he thinks the best throne is your lap. He can be a tad shy at first, but the way to even a royal man's heart is through his stomach and after a treat and a chin scratch, he'll be yours forever! Prince has excellent house manners, as long as no food is left in his reach. He takes treats gently and isn't a jumper, though he will try to climb into your lap on occasion. He's great in his crate and is crated overnight and when the foster leaves. He's not destructive around the house and really only barks when he wants to play or if he sees/hears another dog outside. He is housebroken and has not had a single accident or tried to mark in his foster's home. Outside, Prince loves to zoomie in the snow, play ball, and sniff all of the sniffs. Typical of labs and pits alike, he is a goofy doof and doesn't always watch where he is zooming, so we recommend older kids that he won't risk knocking over. He is working on his leash skills, especially around other animals, but he loves to go for short walks and then back in where it's warm. Prince's ideal home would be with him as the only pet so that he can have all of your love and be the true king of his castle, but can live with other dogs. You see, Prince wasn't treated very well by other dogs in his past. He showed up at the shelter with evidence of a pretty bad dog attack and he was bullied by other dogs for quite a long time. Because of this, he is uncomfortable with having strange dogs in his space, especially if they rush in. With slow introductions, Prince can get along with another respectful and socially savvy dog and would probably enjoy a buddy with the right personality match to play with. Prince can't tell the difference between a cat and a squirrel so his home should have no small animal pets besides fish that he loves to watch swimming around. He would love a moderately active family that will help him shed those extra pounds, explore the world, and then come home for snuggles.

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is sponsored.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Brutus is 8 years old and weighs 28 pounds. He is believed to be a cockerpoo and is a sweet boy. He does have allergies and will require daily medication for them. He is also on a restricted diet, he is allergic to most meat proteins and is eating a rabbit based food.  He is not good with children but seems to be good with other dogs.

All our pets are spayed or neutered, vaccinated including rabies, given de-wormer, heartworm negative or being treated with the slow kill method approved by our veterinarian, on prevention, on flea/tick prevention, most are house trained. The majority but not all of our pets require a fence. Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered. We adopt within 300 miles of New Orleans/Baton Rouge, La and we do not ship or transport--Adoption fee $200. Email us at creolepoodlerescue@yahoo.com to get an adoption application. Complete an adoption form and email it back to us (we do not have a FAX) if interested in adopting and providing a loving home for this pet.  If you can't email it to us, you can mail it to P.O. Box 2333, Gonzales, La 70707, but this will slow the process down.

When you request an adoption application, we will also send you our guidelines to read - many questions you may have are answered there.  All of our pets are in private foster homes. We require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meeting for any of our pets. Everything we know at this time about this pet is posted.IF YOU SEE THIS PET POSTED ON OUR ADOPTABLE PETS PAGE, THIS PET IS AVAILABLE. WE UPDATE OUR ADOPTABLE PETS SEVERAL TIMES DAILY.  IF THE WORD PENDING IS NEXT TO THE NAME, THE PET HAS AN APPROVED ADOPTER COMING TO MEET AND PROBABLY ADOPT HIM OR HER.  We reserve the right to refuse adoption for any reason.

We are all VOLUNTEERS and have full time jobs, families, pets of our own to care for - we do the best that we can to get back to you in a timely manner.  Please realize that turning in an application today will not mean that you adopt a poodle tomorrow.  We believe in taking the time to go through our thorough process to try to match the dog with the family.

Hera's adoption fee is $150 and helps cover her spay, worming, vaccinations, microchip, monthly heart worm, flea and tick preventive and care while at CCHS. animal.description:
We'd like to introduce Tulip!

Tulip is a beautiful 14 month old, Female, American Staffordshire Terrier. This angel was rescued off the streets of San Bernardino emaciated, in heat, and had a prolapsed uterus. This sweet angel is still recovering from her surgery and she would recover quicker if she had a home to relax in. She is otherwise healthy and vaccinated.

This sweet girl loves everyone she meets. She's housebroken, loves sleeping on a comfy dog bed and is very well behaved in the home. She's learning how to walk better on a leash and is perfect in the car. For now, with everything Tulip has been through, we think being the only dog is best. We believe she had to protect herself in the tough streets of San Bernardino and had to be defensive toward other dogs in order to survive.

If you think this absolute gem would be a great fit in your family, please submit a completed adoption application found at www.doggiebonez.com so that we can schedule a meet and greet. He is also on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.

If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short and/or long term doggie foster families. We greatly appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort and safety of a home and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if needed) etc. If you are interested please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

He is settling nicely into his foster home and is slowly getting to know his foster brother. Blake could live with another large female who can tolerate his rough and tumble play style. animal.description:
Hello there, I'm Wiggles! Here are some of my fabulous qualities: I am gorgeous so when we go for walks, the people in the neighborhood will ooh and ahh over your new best friend's handsome good looks. I have flopsy-mopsy ears and a stub of a tail. When I see you, I get really excited and I will shake my butt to show you how happy you make me. 

I'm not super-great yet at knowing how to react when I meet new people that I think might be strangers. I'm still young and I come on strong sometimes. Because I have a territorial instinct, if you like to have a lot of company over to your house, I will need support and training from you so I can warm up to our house guests. With training, I could make a good watch dog and loving companion.

Because of these reasons, the good folks here at Desert Haven think it's best for me to have "an experienced adopter", whatever that means. I think it just means that I'm a really good boy and I need a really good person who can help me learn some really good manners.

I like yummy treats so I am considered "treat motivated". This means I will learn what you teach me but you will probably need to keep a pocketful of biscuits handy. I already know "sit", am learning "down" and after we spend some time bonding I will come to you when you whistle or call for me. I do pull some on the leash so I think it would be good to learn proper leash skills from you.

Here are some of my interests:  I am playful and enjoy toys. I like to carry them around and I will play like tug-o-war with you too. I love going for hikes and walks and being active with you in the out-of-doors.  I like to hunt and search for lizards. I am often on the lookout for something to chase. I am interested in people and being petted and told that I'm a good, good boy. I have extra energy in my body so I need exercise to be happy. I really love your affection but I am sort of awkward about it. I would LOVE to have a patient family that helps me learn to cuddle.

I've told you about me and some of my favorite things. Do you think that I could be one of your favorite things? Come meet me soon! Love you, Wiggles

(Wiggles is about 50 pounds and his date of birth is November of 2018)

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Liv, but friends call me Olive! I’m a bundle of energy and a cuddler to boot! I’m a year and half lab mix, who just may be part jack rabbit. I’m working on my manners, but whenever I meet new people, I just have to kiss their face. I’m convinced that everyone loves me and wants to pet me while I shower them with kisses. 
I especially love to play – fetch and chase are my favorites. I have not met a toy I didn’t like – bonus points if it squeaks or bounces! I know several commands and do well in a kennel (though I prefer human beds). I’m very quick to learn new tricks, but sometimes will be stubborn about listening.
 
When one-on-one, I’m super chill and prefer to nap at their feet, on the bed, in their lap…really as close as you’ll let me. 
I love humans of all sizes, but sometimes forget not to jump on the littlest ones (they fall down easily). I’d do well in a home with friends and space to run and release some of this energy, although I will need to be introduced to any doggy siblings slowly. I refuse to like cats – it’s an ancient rivalry and I refuse to let it go – so please don’t invite them into our home.
 
My love for ice cubes (favorite treat) can only be eclipsed by my love of car rides. I don’t care where we are going (or if I’m invited); all open car doors are an invitation for adventure! Can I take a ride with you?! 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt
(please note: app cannot be done on a mobile device)

For additional information see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

A Good Samaritan noticed a dog scrounging for food in the back roads of south Georgia. This poor dog was not only rooting in the dirt for food but had mud inside of his mouth!! He was clearly starving!!
This Good Samaritan, Jerry, knew he had to save this dog then and there or he would starve. He brought him home and named him Rilee. 
Almost immediately after Rilee was home with Jerry and his wife Betty, he completely started to BLOSSOM into the happiest boy, as you can see!! He knew he was SAFE

Rilee is a total “lap dog”! He absolutely adores humans, will never hesitate to cuddle up and loves planting big kisses on his humans. Rilee’s fosters, Jerry and Betty, have come to nicknaming Rilee “Mr. Prancy Pants” because he loves to prance around, follow his humans, and show off his silly personality! 
Unfortunately, the resident cats and Rilee are not getting along so, Rilee’s bedroom has been the garage and they know he deserves way better! So, we are looking for a FUREVER HOME for this sweet boy! 

Rilee is around 70 lbs, estimated to be 3-4 yrs old. Unfortunately, he is not good with cats or other dogs but is fully house trained, follows commands and is a very LOVING and silly boy. He will be the perfect companion!

*Please note that a fenced yard is required for Rilee

Apply to adopt Rilee at www.twotailzrescue.org!

animal.description:
http://www.greenepets.org/Chico.html
Apply for Chico at the link below.
http://www.greenepets.org/adoption-application.html


Chico is an owner surrender.  He is reactive to UPS trucks, and he was barking at one while the owner kicked him in the butt.  He swung around and nipped the guy in the ankle for the kick.  Boom, no more home. Chico would make a great one or two-person dog in a quiet home.  Or even a home with just adults.

He is very protective of his home and has to be in a crate when guests arrive.

He needs meet n greets with new people on leash.

Other than that, he is a great Only Dog for a family of two.

We recommend further training with him in his new home, in addition to a handler who understands working dogs.

Chico is extremely loving, beautiful, and blows coat twice a year with a vengeance.

Something has happened to this dog that involved a UPS driver because he is off the wall when he encounters one of those trucks.  We strongly feel that Chico was probably maced or bear sprayed at some time or other by a UPS driver.

Chico loves outings, but we will provide a muzzle to keep him out of trouble with people who won't listen to you.

Give this guy a chance, he is really a wonderful dog who has developed some stupid habits that training will correct.

Chico is currently in our detection dog training program.

Amazing Grace Bully Rescue is a foster based rescue in the Pensacola, Florida area. We do not have a physical building. If you would like to meet any of our pups, the first step is to fill out our online application so we can contact you.

If you would like to adopt this Amazing dog, please fill out our online adoption application at www.amazinggracebullyrescue.org

animal.description:
Amelia was saved from a high kill shelter in CA . Just when they wanted to bring the needle in , I managed to get her safe and alive of the shelter . 

Amelia was scared and snapped around her but calmed down over time . 

She had a rough life and I think that she never received any kind of love. Her eyes say it all . 

It is hard to put an age on her because abused and neglected dogs look older so my guess is between 5-7 but she has the spunk of a 3 year old one . 

When i started to walk her , I knew that I was dealing with a TRUE German shepherd . 

These are the precious gems that stick with you and are fiercely loyal . 

Amelia is not good with cats and dogs and would fit in a calm , loving family without kids . 

We hope to find her soon a forever home because this girl is gold . 

Amelia is located in Middle Island NY 

To become her new family please apply today by filling in the adoption application to find on our website www.a-teameliterescuedogs.com or email us and we send you one .

animal.description:
Miles was found as a stray when he crawled into a barn to die.  He was so starving and emaciated that one could see every bone in his body.  

Flash forward a few months and Miles has done a full transformation. He is doing great!  He has gained weight and energy and his personality has blossomed!  He has fantastic house manners; he’s such an easy keeper.  He loves to hang out with us in the house and yard, go for car rides and walks.  We love how sweet and waggly he is when we speak to him!  Miles is a quiet dog at home, but will alert if someone comes onto the property – he’s got a big voice!   Miles loves his things, he will bring you his toys and he keeps them close and will pile them in his crate.    Miles has spent time in supervised doggy play groups and has been social.  We are continuing with training and dog socialization but he needs to go slow!  

Miles is pretty darn close to perfect.  Miles has: amazing house manners, is sugary-sweet and has the pittie wiggles, is an undemanding cuddler and all around easy keeper!   If you’d like to meet Miles give us a call or text 707-972-9359 or 530-570-4538 and fill out an application at https://www.mendoshelterpets.org/

animal.description:
Brett is a VERY sweet dog that came into the city shelter with an injured leg.   It turned out to be a torn ACL, which is difficult to mend in a shelter environment, so FOMAS brought him into rescue and had it surgically repaired.  He has been in foster/boarding and continues to recover. He has finished his doctor visits.  Now he needs a home of his own where he will enjoy walks and play, preferably in a fenced yard or with regular supervised activity in a dog park.

He happily plays with other dogs and loves people.  He does well in his kennel, but is happiest just laying by (or in) the doorway watching the world.  He is not particularly interested in cats and gets along with dogs, though does not play very energetically.

Brett is about 4 years old, current on vaccinations, neutered and microchipped.  He is heartworm positive, but has been given an initial treatment and a 6 month preventative, and is expected to become negative over time if he remains on preventative.  Please message our page to arrange to meet him.

animal.description:
Meet Sawyer! He is a Beagle mix, and his estimated date of birth is April 2020. He is 34lb as of 1/16/20. The perfect size!

Sawyer was adopted by a loving family over the summer but due to some unforeseen circumstances, he unfortunately needs to be re-homed due to no fault of his own. He is a sweet sweet, high energy boy, who would do great in a home with another active dog who can be his buddy. This boy is not a couch potato! This boy also LOVES apples, so anyone willing to share an apple with him is high on his list.

He is great with other dogs, and just full of love. He goes to doggy daycare twice a week and does amazing, so a home where he gets an outlet like that would be ideal. He needs to work on his obedience since he is a still puppy, but all love. A home with small kids may not be great for him since he is an exuberant greeter (he may knock little ones over by mistake!).

He is currently located in Wethersfield CT.
*please note, his video is from when he was 4 months old! The pictures are recent!*

His adoption fee is $290

**Please note: Due to state-specific import laws, we are not able to adopt to residents of Rhode Island, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, or Maine.

You can find his application here.
www.humanesocietyofthedelta.org/adopt


--------------------------------------------------------------------------

                             ADOPTION FEE AND HEALTH INFORMATION

His adoption fee and transport combined is $490: This covers age appropriate vaccines (2 DHPP vaccine), (Bordetella vaccine), (Rabies vaccine if 12 weeks and older), up to date on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, bi-weekly worming, microchip, fostering costs, health certificate and transportation fees.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

                                       FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS

Q: Where is he located?
A: He is currently in a foster home but is originally from our shelter in Arkansas.

Q: It feels scary adopting without meeting the pup first. What if he isn't the right fit for our home?
A: We know it can feel scary and that's why we offer a FULL refund of your adoption fee within the first two weeks if for some reason it's not the right fit. We want our adopters to feel confident and we want the best situation for our pups.  If in that 2 weeks you feel it is not working out, we can rehome the dog and refund your adoption fee.  All we ask is that you foster the dog until we find them a new home! 

Q: I have more questions!! Who do I contact?
A:  Please e-mail adopt@humanesocietyofthedelta.org directly.  We DO NOT answer adoption questions or inquiries on any other platform.

Q: I am under 21, will you adopt to me?
A: Unfortunately, we do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21.

Q: I would like to surprise my family with a puppy!  Can I do this?
A:  Unfortunately, no.  If there is more than one decision-maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement. 


Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

animal.description:
Boss is maybe about 8 years old,- He weighs 12 lbs and is muscular, not a fragile little flower! His owner was older and could no longer take proper care of him and as a result, he is more than likely best fit with a single woman owner.  Boss is the Boss of the house. Hw would not be a good choice for apartment living or living where you see new people a lot. He is a Chihuahua! He is very vocal when meeting new people-especially men. Men are not Boss's thing. Once he knows people, he settles down and is ok. He does not like joggers and he doesn't like people on bikes. I think in his mind they are running away from him so he must try to chase them.
Boss  gets along fine with the other pups in the house. He  resource guards his toys and chew bones, so when he is with other dogs, those items must be supervised. He gets along fine with other dogs , so meeting dogs on walks  is fine, he just is the boss of his territory and his toys. He likes to cuddle up and keep you company while napping. He likes playing with stuffed toys and will drag them around the house. and try to take them on walks. He will fetch them if you throw them. He walks well on leash, and rides well in a car. His butt wiggles a million miles an hour when he is excited or happy and he listens well if you tell him to come or stop. He will jump up next to you and throw himself backwards to get a belly rub. His belly is soft and smooth and I love giving him belly rubs!  I have cats and Boss is ok with them-he chases my one cat every once in awhile, I think when he is bored;-) but stops if I tell him to. He has a lot of personality! I feel that Boss will do best in a quiet home and one Mom. Apartments would be dicey because of the constant flow of meeting people. And a busy area would also be dicey since he likes to chase moving cars, bikes and joggers. 
Boss is a wonderful guy and needs a mama that understands chichi's and their behaviors. If you have the patience to give him a little time to get to know you you will have a fun and entertaining buddy for life! 


If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website-?www.luckymuttsrescue.org?and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.
 We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions. 
 Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  
Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  
Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.  
 Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 
Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. 
Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  
Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen. We receive several applications for each dog. 
Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.  
 Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will
be in active status for a period of six months. 
 We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  
Should you see a dog that interests you,please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

Weight: 50 lbs

Dog Friendly: Yes
Cat Friendly: Yes
Kid Friendly: Unknown

My name is Becky. I enjoy walks of any duration, and chasing other dogs who happen to be running away from me. I'm fast like a bunny and yes, I hop like a bunny too. I am especially fond of burying my food in my bedding and licking everything when I'm excited and happy. I feel safe in my kennel and it's usually my favorite place to be, even if you leave it open.

Becky is a rather skittish girl. She is slow to trust, but when she's comfortable she can be very adorable and affectionate. She will need a family that is calm and patient, especially at first when she's figuring out the pattern of her new home. A doggy friend or two of similar size and compatible temperament would be advantageous to help pull her out of her shell.

Adoption Fee: $200 - Includes Spay/Neuter, Microchip, and UTD on all vaccines.

BENNY WOULD LOVE TO BE IN A FOSTER HOME WHILE HE IS WAITING TO BE ADOPTED. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN FOSTERING OR ADOPTING BENNY, PLEASE GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE FACEBOOK PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS.

Benny is a very handsome 2 year old Terrier mix. He is so sweet and loves to give kisses. He loves to go for walks as well as hang out and do whatever you are doing. MUST BE ONLY DOG!! He needs another dog in his forever home to play with. Unfortunately, we do not know how he is with cats. He would do best with children 10 years old or older. Benny's forever home must have a fenced yard where he can safely run, play and hang out with his people. He is neutered, up to date on his vaccinations, on heart worm preventative as well as house and crate trained. Benny is looking forward to becoming a very loved member of a forever family.

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters. Benny's adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

*All applicants must have a vet reference and a fenced yard to be considered.*

Hello lucky lottery winner!!! No- not really a lottery, but you will feel like you have hit the jackpot if I choose you to be my forever home. So let's talk about me and see if we could be a family.

My name is Toi. I am a Min Pin/Chihuahua mix who is 10 1/2 years old. Don't let that age thing bother you,, I am a medium energy dog who loves walks, zoomies in the backyard with my foster sister and brother and car rides. My favorite word is Treats!!!

I am a little bit choosey about who I do and don't like. Foster mom says I need some more "socialization:"- whatever that means. Hey- do you instantly like everyone you meet? I bet you don't. I choose to think of myself as discerning about who I let into my inner circle!! But just think how special you will feel when I decide that you are deserving of my trust, snuggles and love. I didn't get to meet a lot of people when I was growing up and it takes me a while to let my guard down with new humans. I do best when I am on a leash when new two-leggers come into the house. I can be growly, but if they leave me alone, I leave them alone. I listen to Mom when she tells me "Toi, settle down, don't be growly, you're fine".

My foster home has two other dogs in it, so I have a foster brother and sister who are my best friends. We love to run around the backyard together, wait for our treats, mealtime and jump into the big bed every morning.. My favorite place to sleep at night is on a chair covered in my blankets in the big bedroom. I need lots of blankets so I can burrow down inside of them!!

Children aren't really my thing, so foster mom says we are looking for a home with adults only. And my new family needs to be very experienced with dogs who need a little extra attention, time and patience. Do you know the saying, "good things come to those who wait" or "patience is a virtue"? Or how about- just love me for who I am, just like I will love you for who you are and together we will grow and become the best we can be.

Am I a lap dog? No. Am I going to instantly trust you? No. Am I worth the work you will put into building a relationship with me? You bet!! And on top of that- I am very handsome. So maybe it's okay that I play a little "hard to get"!

This is what I need from my new family:

A big fenced in backyard so I can run and run and run. At least one other dog to be my bestie and to show me how to be a dog. Someone who can understand that while I love to lay right next to my human, I am not one of those silly lap dogs

who wants to be held like a baby. Maybe some day, but not right now. Someone who loves me unconditionally and will take the time to earn my love and trust.

Adults who are experienced with dogs who have fear and socialization issues.

And don't forget about toys- I need lots of toys!! Toys to carry around, toys to throw up in the air, toys to chase- you can never have too many toys!! But mostly time, love and patience.

So let's get those applications rolling in and I can pick out my new home!!! I'm posting some new pics that foster mom took of me and I know they make me look irresistible!!!

Toi's adoption donation is $250.00
1/3/21 9:34 AM
