animal.description:
Meet Negrita!

ATTENTION: PLEASE READ THROUGH TO SEE WHETHER YOU MEET OUR ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE RESPONDING. IF YOU MEET OUR CRITERIA FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE FOLLOW THE LINK TOWARD THE BOTTOM OF THE PROFILE TO COMPLETE OUR ONLINE APPLICATION. THANK YOU!

Negrita was living as a street dog in Mexico. She was hit by a car that fractured her spine when she was about one year old. At that time, she was completely paralyzed and dragging herself around on the streets (see pic). Luckily, a kind person rescued her from a life on the streets. She was extremely thin and fearful. The woman knew there was very little chance of finding her a home in Mexico so she searched for a rescue in the US to take her. That’s where we stepped in. 

Negrita was extremely underweight when she arrived in Oregon. Her hind legs were very atrophied. We started physical therapy and within the first month, she gained weight and was able to get up on her rear legs and walk. She can’t feel her feet, and she walks with them rolled over, but she can walk, and she wants to walk, even though it’s not normal walking. She was eventually even able to run in the grass. So awesome!! 

Negrita doesn’t have complete bladder or bowel control, but we don’t put her in a diaper. She needs to be expressed 3-4 times a day to go potty. She needs someone who is committed to this routine. If she is routinely expressed she does not have any “accidents”.

Negrita does fine with other dogs as long as they don’t jump on her. She is understandably worried about that when she meets a new dog. She loves having a calm dog companion. 

Negrita is sweet and loving with all people. She loves attention and greets her humans with an adorable “woo woo woo”. She is now approximately two years old. 

Negrita can manage one or two stairs off a porch or deck but should live in a single-story home such as ranch style. She would not be able to manage a two story home.


Adoption Process: We are not first come first served. Indigo Rescue focuses on finding good matches between dogs and families to ensure life long adoptions. We deliver all dogs to their new homes. All of our dogs are in foster homes. 

If you’re interested in meeting one of our dogs, please use the following link and complete our Adoption Application. You can either scan your completed application and email it to us at: info@indigorescue.org, or you can fax it to us at: 888-502-7660.
The link is not live, so you will need to copy and paste it into your browser: https://storage.googleapis.com/gator-users/user-680788/documents/d1742bff02e44c2ea25649cb45df5103/Pet%20Application%20Form%20December%202020.pdf
If the dog you're interested in seems compatible with your lifestyle we'll set up a time for you to meet the dog privately.
PLEASE NOTE: Indigo Rescue only adopts to homes within 30 miles of Beaverton because our volunteers deliver all of our dogs to their adoptive homes. We work very hard to create a family of our Indigo Rescue adopters because we want to be close enough to help in case there are any problems. We want everyone to be happy and successful!

**ALL of our dogs, puppies, cats, kittens and rabbits come vaccined to their age, spayed/neutered and microchipped.

Thank you for your interest in adopting and saving a life.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Milo! I am a sweet, gentle giant who joined PPITS recently after my former owner had a stroke and the family didn't want me. I have been in and out of foster homes and will soon go to boarding because my current foster mom won't be able to keep me much longer.

It has been quite a journey that has affected me a lot. I don't want to be alone anymore. I am a good boy! I don't get along well with other dogs so I should be in an only dog home. I love going on walks, playing with my toys, and giving puppy hugs and kisses. Due to my size, I would do best with older children.
I am looking for someone who understands that my world was turned upside down and that I need some time to feel safe and secure. Will that be you?

animal.description:
INKY loves people. At his foster home he is crate trained, uses a doggie door and walks using a face halter. Affectionate, great family dog. 

Revised adoption policy:
Due to Covid -19 pandemic and social distancing requirements, we've temporarily revised our adoption policy. First, please email (desertpawsnm@gmail.com) to inquire before you fill out the online application. We are unable to do meetgreets or adoption events at this time or bring multiple animals to your house to choose from, so please only inquire if you're serious about adopting this particular animal. If you're just shopping around with several shelters and rescues please let us know. If you're application is approved (which could take up to one week to process because we are working with many other animals on a daily basis) then we will email/text/call to discuss and set up a day/time to bring the pet to you. We may ask you to send us pics /video since we can't come into the home for the meet/greet. Dog meetings are preferred in neutral territory (walk on the street), progressing to backyard (no toys, no food to possess over), then to inside the house (making sure no one accidentally gets boxed into a corner). Because of Covid, you will most likely have to do these activities while you FaceTime/Duo, etc us from the vehicle. At the meeting/adoption at your house (outside) please wear a mask (as will we) and use hand sanitizer.

We adopt to the Santa Fe, Abq, Los Alamos, Rio Rancho areas. If you are outside of these areas, please don't apply.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET PLEASE SUBMIT THE ADOPTION APPLICATION VIA OUR WEBSITE: WWW.TAILSOFHOPEDOGRESCUE.COM. THANK YOU! ADOPTION IS $150.00.


This handsome guy is Grape! He was adopted from a shelter and then approx. two weeks later was found hit by a car. His adopter was contacted and chose not to reclaim him. So we went in and got him. He had a fracture to his elbow then was discovered upon xrays. He was then crate confined to allow healing, which it did! 

We estimate his date of birth to be around November 15, 2019. This sweet boy is fully vaccinated, microchipped, tested negative for heartworms and is current on heartworm and flea prevention. He is great with other dogs, due to his age would need another dog in the home,  loves people and is crate trained. He has the sweetest disposition and would make any family a wonderful furry addition! Especially of they have children! Our best guess for breed is a Black Lab mix, which as most people know are great family dogs. 
Grape is located in a Memphis area foster home.

animal.description:
My name is Brody and I am estimated to be just over a year old now. Life started out for me living in a cage. I had to stand in my own filth day after day, sometimes I didn't get fed, but one day I was liberated. I have come a long way since then!

I love spending time with my foster family. I have a lot of energy so my foster mom takes me out running and that is wonderful! After a nice long run we come home and snuggle on the sofa and then I get to do something I absolutely love: I get to watch tv! I am fascinated by it. True crime shows are a favorite of mine. I'd love to be a dog detective!

I would be just fine as a single dog but if there are other dogs in the home I would do best with a female who will put me in my place. I would not do well with another male dog.

I am loving and sweet and very much want to please my people. That's very important to me. I do get car sick. I love to go for walks or running.

My forever family must have prior current Doberman experience so they know and understand what goes into training and working with a young Doberman. They must also agree to take me to obedience training classes. Please review the adoption rules. If you qualify and are interested in adopting Brody, please place an application by : CLICKING HERE

Please help me to find my forever home!

All of our dogs are current with all shots, are on heart worm preventative monthly and are neutered/spayed. All dogs are tail docked. All of the above Dobes are pure breed Dobermans unless otherwise noted.We hope you can find a place in your heart and your home for one of our rescue Dobes.Please Note:In most cases we require a fenced yard.We do not place our rescue dogs in homes with very young children (under the age of 8 years). We set these limitations, not because of aggression issues with our dogs, but because Dobermans are generally large, active dogs and can easily knock down, run over or easily trip a small child, causing a serious fall. Also, we reserve the right to refuse adoption for any reason.Our adoption area encompasses Nebraska, Iowa and South Dakota.Copyright 2007 - Omaha Doberman RescueFor more information or to fill out an adoption request please visithttp://www.doberescue-ne.org/ 1/25/21 9:23 AM

animal.description:
Sweet old man Deacon came in to rescue with ruptured ligaments in his rear legs. After surgery and some TLC from his foster mom he is feeling better and ready for a home of his own. He's a calm, older gentlemen who loves to nap and snuggle.
Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label. Each dog in our rescue is in a loving foster home, where they can grow, play, and recover from their time spent on the streets or in a shelter. If you'd like to meet an adoptable dog, please fill out an application on our website, www.edcr.org. Because we are a foster home based rescue a completed adoption application is required to meet our adoptable dogs.

animal.description: Hi! I'm Pebbles! I'm about 5 years old & I love belly rubs! My foster mom laughs because when I get excited, I run around with my butt tucked up under me, doing zoomies around the yard. I don't really care for girl dogs but I will admit I have a little crush on my foster mom's big red boy. There are cats in my foster home but when they come into my space, I try my best to get them. Foster mom says cats are pets, not food. I don't get it, though. I also refuse to share anything with anybody else. I've lived in a place where I had to fight to survive, so nope. Not happening. My bowl, my treat, my food. I do dream of having my very own human who will accept me for who I am. Somebody to cuddle with & rub my belly; tell me what a good girl I am; love me unconditionally. I'm really kinda adorable. Like a tiny rottie with a blue coat. And, a face that's always searching your eyes, for a reason to make you smile.

animal.description:
Meet Brock! We are pretty sure that this boy is actually a fish disguised as a dog!! He certainly lives for life on the water! Brock likes the active lifestyle, walking, hiking, and you guessed it - swimming, swimming, and more swimming! What a fun fella for the outdoorsman! Check out the video of Brock taking a swim in the Appomattox River! What a ham, he's having a blast!  Into playing fetch at the lake or river or maybe even the beach? If so, Brock would like to apply to be your best friend and hang out buddy! Come meet Brock today!

NOTE: In regards to children and pets, it is always best to remember that while pulling, tugging, poking, and pinching are all normal behaviors of a small child exploring the things around him, these behaviors can become frustrating for animals to tolerate. In response to pain or becoming overly annoyed, ANY animal can be subject to BITE, The pet and human relationship is an amazing bond that all pet lovers of all ages should be able to experience. As animal advocates and animal lovers, we want that experience to be an enjoyable one for every family that acquires a pet, therefore we always strongly recommend that parents/custodians of children (1) always monitor the interactions of their pets and their children, (2) never leave small children unattended with pets, (3) spend quality time teaching children how to be gentle with pets, respect the pet's personal space, and recognize behaviors that, even if they are not intended to be, are indeed bothersome to the animal and (4) be willing to set boundaries for children against behaviors that may be perceived by the pet as being annoying, fretful, or painful. Never underestimate the willingness of an animal to set boundaries on what it will not tolerate. When the responsibility of boundary setting is put upon the animal, it is usually carried out by nipping, snapping, and biting.
Remember, YOU are the parent/custodian and YOU are the pack leader and thus YOU are the one responsible for making sure your "kiddos," both two- legged and four, can live happily, safely, and harmoniously together.

animal.description:
Hazel is a Great Pyrenees and Malamute mix. She is a very special girl who has epilepsy that is being controlled with medication.

Hazel was taken to Texas A & M to be evaluated by the best veterinarians in the state. They performed an MRI as well as several other tests to try to determine the cause of her seizures. The tests found nothing abnormal about her brain and no sign of any disease that could cause her seizures.

Hazel is very gentle, sweet, and independent. She gets along well with all of my dogs as well as all fosters that I've had. She is bell trained, doggy door trained and fully house trained. 

Hazel needs a special adopter who will work in conjunction with a veterinarian to maintain her health and control her epilepsy. Her current medications cost roughly $150 per month at Kroger with their discount card. She also takes CBD oil twice a day. 

Hazel would love to meet you! Won't you give this sweet girl a chance?

Hazel is available for introductions by appointment as she is currently living with a foster family. PLEASE EMAIL dogadoptteam@aartexas.org TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT


Est. DOB: 11/23/18
63 lbs.
AAR does not transport for adoption

animal.description: Mocha has been looking for her forever home since November 2019! She was surrendered to us during a week of freezing temperatures and snow. She had been kept tied outside almost 24/7, and was in danger of freezing to death. She was also abused by family members who threw rocks at her and beat her. We scrambled to take her in, and since then we've learned a lot about this sweet girl. She's highly trainable, loving, playful, and has shown us how resilient she is. She's 4 years old and weighs 60 pounds. She would like to be the only animal in the home, with only older kids. She's insanely snuggly, and her favorite place to be is the couch or in bed with you! She's versatile and just as happy to be going on hiking adventures as she is chilling on the couch. She loves car rides! She'd do best in a quiet household with not a lot going on. She likes to run around the yard and get her roomies out, so a fenced in yard is a strong recommendation. She loves just lounging in the sun and hanging out outside. She's even good with baths and getting her nails trimmed! She's crate trained but isn't destructive in the home at all. She's EXTREMELY intelligent and trainable, and is super food motivated! This girl is a rockstar with her tricks and learns them so quickly. This dog is one of a kind and when she knows you're her person she'll be your best friend for life.
animal.name: Mocha

Ryley can be seen at our adoption event or at our adoption event or by appointment to approved applicants. For more information, please visit http://FurrEverPetsRescue.org  or call (9 a.m.-8 p.m.)/text Ione Fried, (903) 918-3213.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Handsome Lincoln is just a big puppy, about 10 mos old when we got him off the streets in March. He will forever be a bit traumatized from whatever happened to him while he was homeless, living outside of Lincoln Elementary School in San Bernardino.
He is a playful, silly boy, always on high alert, and still jumps when a sudden movement startles him. He went to boot camp training for 6 weeks where he mastered all his basic commands and his trainer said he is incredibly smart and athletic. You should see the flips and twirls this boy will do to catch balls midair! He is a total working dog, so he needs lots of mental and physical stimulation, so he'snot your average family dog -- rather than cuddle on the couch, he'd rather sniff around the yard searching for his tennis balls or whatever else he decides to sniff out.
Lincoln is looking for a large, power-breed experienced owner. Because he can be easily spooked, a home with no kids or kids over 16 required. Active home a must.
Adopt Lincoln! See his adoption page here: http://www.causeforsbpaws.org/animals/browse

animal.description:
Emma is a 1.5 year old Pit Bull Terrier Mix who was surrendered to the SPCA of East Texas. She is a great dog who is housebroken and knows basic commands like "sit." You can even trust to her stay inside without being crated for the entire workday. Emma is treat motivated and is a gentle treat taker. She is currently working on "leave it" and "heel." She walks well on a leash otherwise. She has the sweetest personality. She is still very much a puppy temperament and loves to play fetch or with other big dogs. She is a high energy dog and will need someone to walk her regularly or a large yard to play in. She should be fed separately from other dogs. She needs to be in a home without little dogs or cats. Emma is truly a well mannered girl and is desperate for a family that she can show this to.

For adoption: www.spcaeasttx.com
For more information: Adopt@spcaeasttx.com

animal.description: Jersey is a 7.5 year old male mixed breed. He weighs 60 pounds. Jersey was transferred from a county shelter so we do not have information about his previous household. When he arrived at our shelter Jersey was heartworm positive but he has since completed his heartworm treatment. We have had mixed reactions when introducing Jersey to other dogs at the shelter. We always recommend a meet and greet with any resident dogs. Jersey has been on a slumber party during which he was introduced to resident cats which he chased excessively. At this time we don't believe Jersey would do well living with cats. Jersey was also on a slumber party with a child and reportedly did well. We always recommend a meet and greet with any children in the household or children that visit often, such as grandkids. Please call for more information or to make an appointment to meet Jersey. (Updated 1/30/21).

animal.description: Hi there! Im Frosty. Im a big floof who is looking for a calm home with dog savvy owners. I am super smart, if I do say so myself! Im loyal and loving, but not clingy- I like my independence. Some of my likes are: sniffing, walks, chicken, squeaky toys, and fetch. animal.description: Cheddar is a unilateral deaf dog. He went through 2 weeks of training with the deaf dog rescue of america, trainer Mark Tipton. Cheddar has been working on eye-contact and engagement. Cheddar is crate trained and potty trained, but needs a firm and confident owner, that understands the needs of a deaf dog. Cheddar does fine with other dogs, and even cats (you can see videos of him engaging with other dogs and cats on our instagram page). But - being a deaf dog, Cheddar needs extra time to decompress each day as he can become amped up and moody, this is where his crate training comes in handy. He walks well on leash and knows basic commands through sign language. Cheddar needs an owner that can set boundaries and a schedule, and stick to them. Cheddar has been around young children but because he can sometimes be territorial over his food bowl when eating, we suggest a home with older kids if any. Please fill out and application on our website if you feel like you are capable of giving Cheddar the forever home he needs.

animal.description: Bo Woods had a rough start to life. He jumped homes multiple times before he landed here with us at Daphneyland. We are working on behavioral issues that he has gained over time from bouncing around multiple homes. Bo Woods is a handsome boy but needs a very specific type of home; no men in the home, no other animals and someone who will have to work with a trainer of our choosing. Since Bo Woods will need to work with one of our trainers we will need someone who is local to the Southern California area. If you think Bo Woods or any of the 50+ hounds here at Daphneyland would be a good fit for you submit an adoption application at www.daphneyland.com
